[src:pod-disruption-budgets/availability] Normally high availability systems might be specified as 99.98%, 99.999% or 99.9996%.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/availability] The converse, **unavailability**, is 1 minus the availability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/availability] Average availability must be defined on an interval of the real line.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/availability] Availability is the probability that an item will be in an operable and committable state at the start of a mission when the mission is called for at a random time, and is generally defined as uptime divided by total time (uptime plus downtime).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/availability] Let's say a series component is composed of components A, B and C.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/availability] Therefore, the combined availability of multiple components in a series is always lower than the availability of individual components.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/availability] Using parallel components can exponentially increase the availability of the overall system.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/availability] For example, if each of your hosts has only 50% availability, by using 10 of hosts in parallel, you can achieve 99.9023% availability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/availability] Note that redundancy doesn’t always lead to higher availability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/availability] In fact, redundancy increases complexity, which in turn reduces availability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/availability] Your system can reliably scale out and scale in redundant components.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/availability] Furthermore, these methods are capable of identifying the most critical items and failure modes or events that impact availability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/availability] The impact of a one-off/non-repairable element (could be refurbished/remanufactured) on the availability of the system, in which it operates, equals the mean time to failure (MTTF)/(MTTF + the mean time to repair MTTR).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/availability] It is based on quantities under the control of the designer.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/availability] Outage due to equipment in hours per year = 1/rate = 1/MTTF = 0.01235 hours per year.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/availability] Availability measures are classified by either the time interval of interest or the mechanisms for the system downtime.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/availability] If the time interval of interest is the primary concern, we consider instantaneous, limiting, average, and limiting average availability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/availability] The aforementioned definitions are developed in Barlow and Proschan [1975], Lie, Hwang, and Tillman [1977], and Nachlas [1998].
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/availability] The second primary classification for availability is contingent on the various mechanisms for downtime, such as the inherent availability, achieved availability, and operational availability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/availability] Mi [1998] gives some comparison results of availability considering inherent availability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/availability] A very comprehensive recent book is by Trivedi and Bobbio [2017].
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/availability] Availability factor is used extensively in power plant engineering.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/availability] For example, the North American Electric Reliability Corporation implemented the Generating Availability Data System in 1982.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] This page shows how to limit the number of concurrent disruptions that your application experiences, allowing for higher availability while permitting the cluster administrator to manage the clusters nodes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] Your Kubernetes server must be at or later than version v1.21.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] To check the version, enter `kubectl version`.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] Think about how your application reacts to disruptions.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] Create the PDB object from the YAML file.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] In this case, make a note of the controller's `.spec.selector`; the same selector goes into the PDBs `.spec.selector`.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] From version 1.15 PDBs support custom controllers where the scale subresource is enabled.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] You can also use PDBs with pods which are not controlled by one of the above controllers, or arbitrary groups of pods, but there are some restrictions, described in Arbitrary workloads and arbitrary selectors.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] Decide how many instances can be down at the same time for a short period due to a voluntary disruption.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] Values for `minAvailable` or `maxUnavailable` can be expressed as integers or as a percentage.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] When you specify the value as a percentage, it may not map to an exact number of Pods.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] For example, if you have 7 Pods and you set `minAvailable` to `"50%"`, it's not immediately obvious whether that means 3 Pods or 4 Pods must be available.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] Kubernetes rounds up to the nearest integer, so in this case, 4 Pods must be available.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] When you specify the value `maxUnavailable` as a percentage, Kubernetes rounds up the number of Pods that may be disrupted.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] Thereby a disruption can exceed your defined `maxUnavailable` percentage.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] You can examine the code that controls this behavior.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] The behavior for an empty selector differs between the policy/v1beta1 and policy/v1 APIs for PodDisruptionBudgets.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] For policy/v1beta1 an empty selector matches zero pods, while for policy/v1 an empty selector matches every pod in the namespace.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] You can specify only one of `maxUnavailable` and `minAvailable` in a single `PodDisruptionBudget`.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] `maxUnavailable` can only be used to control the eviction of pods that all have the same associated controller managing them.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] In the examples below, "desired replicas" is the `scale` of the controller managing the pods being selected by the `PodDisruptionBudget`.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] Example 1: With a `minAvailable` of 5, evictions are allowed as long as they leave behind 5 or more healthy pods among those selected by the PodDisruptionBudget's `selector`.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] Example 2: With a `minAvailable` of 30%, evictions are allowed as long as at least 30% of the number of desired replicas are healthy.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] Example 3: With a `maxUnavailable` of 5, evictions are allowed as long as there are at most 5 unhealthy replicas among the total number of desired replicas.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] Example 4: With a `maxUnavailable` of 30%, evictions are allowed as long as the number of unhealthy replicas does not exceed 30% of the total number of desired replica rounded up to the nearest integer.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] If the total number of desired replicas is just one, that single replica is still allowed for disruption, leading to an effective unavailability of 100%.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] In typical usage, a single budget would be used for a collection of pods managed by a controller—for example, the pods in a single ReplicaSet or StatefulSet.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] A disruption budget does not truly guarantee that the specified number/percentage of pods will always be up.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] For example, a node that hosts a pod from the collection may fail when the collection is at the minimum size specified in the budget, thus bringing the number of available pods from the collection below the specified size.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] The budget can only protect against voluntary evictions, not all causes of unavailability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] If you set `maxUnavailable` to 0% or 0, or you set `minAvailable` to 100% or the number of replicas, you are requiring zero voluntary evictions.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] When you set zero voluntary evictions for a workload object such as ReplicaSet, then you cannot successfully drain a Node running one of those Pods.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] If you try to drain a Node where an unevictable Pod is running, the drain never completes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] This is permitted as per the semantics of `PodDisruptionBudget`.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] You can find examples of pod disruption budgets defined below.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] They match pods with the label `app: zookeeper`.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] For example, if the above `zk-pdb` object selects the pods of a StatefulSet of size 3, both specifications have the exact same meaning.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] The use of `maxUnavailable` is recommended as it automatically responds to changes in the number of replicas of the corresponding controller.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] You can create or update the PDB object using kubectl.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] Use kubectl to check that your PDB is created.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] The non-zero value for `ALLOWED DISRUPTIONS` means that the disruption controller has seen the pods, counted the matching pods, and updated the status of the PDB.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] The current implementation considers healthy pods, as pods that have `.status.conditions` item with `type="Ready"` and `status="True"`.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] These pods are tracked via `.status.currentHealthy` field in the PDB status.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] PodDisruptionBudget guarding an application ensures that `.status.currentHealthy` number of pods does not fall below the number specified in `.status.desiredHealthy` by disallowing eviction of healthy pods.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] By using `.spec.unhealthyPodEvictionPolicy`, you can also define the criteria when unhealthy pods should be considered for eviction.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] The default behavior when no policy is specified corresponds to the `IfHealthyBudget` policy.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] This policy ensures that running pods of an already disrupted application have the best chance to become healthy.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] This has negative implications for draining nodes, which can be blocked by misbehaving applications that are guarded by a PDB.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] More specifically applications with pods in `CrashLoopBackOff` state (due to a bug or misconfiguration), or pods that are just failing to report the `Ready` condition.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] ), but not yet healthy are considered disrupted and can be evicted regardless of whether the criteria in a PDB is met.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] This means prospective running pods of a disrupted application might not get a chance to become healthy.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] By using this policy, cluster managers can easily evict misbehaving applications that are guarded by a PDB.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] phase are always considered for eviction.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] You can skip this section if you only use PDBs with the built-in workload resources (Deployment, ReplicaSet, StatefulSet and ReplicationController) or with custom resources that implement a `scale` subresource, and where the PDB selector exactly matches the selector of the Pod's owning resource.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] It is not possible to use other availability configurations, because Kubernetes cannot derive a total number of pods without a supported owning resource.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] You can use a selector which selects a subset or superset of the pods belonging to a workload resource.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] The eviction API will disallow eviction of any pod covered by multiple PDBs, so most users will want to avoid overlapping selectors.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/configure-pdb] One reasonable use of overlapping PDBs is when pods are being transitioned from one PDB to another.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance specifically refers to a system's capability to handle faults without any degradation or downtime.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] In the event of an error, end-users remain unaware of any issues.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Conversely, a system that experiences errors with some interruption in service or graceful degradation of performance is termed 'resilient'.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] In resilience, the system adapts to the error, maintaining service but acknowledging a certain impact on performance.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Typically, fault tolerance describes computer systems, ensuring the overall system remains functional despite hardware or software issues.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Non-computing examples include structures that retain their integrity despite damage from fatigue, corrosion or impact.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] The first known fault-tolerant computer was SAPO, built in 1951 in Czechoslovakia by Antonín Svoboda.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Its basic design was magnetic drums connected via relays, with a voting method of memory error detection (triple modular redundancy).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Several other machines were developed along this line, mostly for military use.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Computers with a high amount of runtime that would be under heavy use, such as many of the supercomputers used by insurance companies for their probability monitoring.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Most of the development in the so-called LLNM (Long Life, No Maintenance) computing was done by NASA during the 1960s, in preparation for Project Apollo and other research aspects.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] NASA's first machine went into a space observatory, and their second attempt, the JSTAR computer, was used in Voyager.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] This computer had a backup of memory arrays to use memory recovery methods and thus it was called the Jet Propulsion Laboratory Self-Testing-And-Repairing computer.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] It could detect its own errors and fix them or use redundant modules as needed.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] The computer is still working, as of early 2022.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Hyper-dependable computers were pioneered mostly by aircraft manufacturers, nuclear power companies, and the railroad industry in the United States.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] These entities needed computers with massive amounts of uptime that would fail gracefully enough during a fault to allow continued operation, while relying on constant human monitoring of computer output to detect faults.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] IBM developed the first computer of this kind for NASA for guidance of Saturn V rockets.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Later, BNSF, Unisys, and General Electric built their own.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] In the 1970s, much work happened in the field.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] For instance, F14 CADC had built-in self-test and redundancy.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] In general, the early efforts at fault-tolerant designs were focused mainly on internal diagnosis, where a fault would indicate something was failing and a worker could replace it.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] SAPO, for instance, had a method by which faulty memory drums would emit a noise before failure.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Later efforts showed that to be fully effective, the system had to be self-repairing and diagnosing – isolating a fault and then implementing a redundant backup while alerting a need for repair.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] This is known as N-model redundancy, where faults cause automatic fail-safes and a warning to the operator, and it is still the most common form of level one fault-tolerant design in use today.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Voting was another initial method, as discussed above, with multiple redundant backups operating constantly and checking each other's results.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] For example, if four components reported an answer of 5 and one component reported an answer of 6, the other four would "vote" that the fifth component was faulty and have it taken out of service.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] This is called M out of N majority voting.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Historically, the trend has been to move away from N-model and toward M out of N, as the complexity of systems and the difficulty of ensuring the transitive state from fault-negative to fault-positive did not disrupt operations.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers, in 1976 and Stratus Technologies were among the first companies specializing in the design of fault-tolerant computer systems for online transaction processing.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Hardware fault tolerance sometimes requires that broken parts be removed and replaced with new parts while the system is still operational (in computing known as *hot swapping*).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Such a system implemented with a single backup is known as **single point tolerant** and represents the vast majority of fault-tolerant systems.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] In such systems the mean time between failures should be long enough for the operators to have sufficient time to fix the broken devices (mean time to repair) before the backup also fails.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] It is helpful if the time between failures is as long as possible, but this is not specifically required in a fault-tolerant system.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance is notably successful in computer applications.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers built their entire business on such machines, which used single-point tolerance to create their NonStop systems with uptimes measured in years.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Fail-safe architectures may encompass also the computer software, for example by process replication.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Data formats may also be designed to degrade gracefully.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Hyper Text Markup Language (HTML) for example, is designed to be forward compatible, allowing Web browsers to ignore new and unsupported HTML entities without causing the document to be unusable.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Additionally, proper user interface design mandates that websites provide an optional lightweight front end that does not rely on JavaScript and has a minimal layout, to ensure wide accessibility and outreach.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] A highly fault-tolerant system might continue at the same level of performance even though one or more components have failed.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] For example, a building with a backup electrical generator will provide the same voltage to wall outlets even if the grid power fails.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] A system that is designed to fail safe, or fail-secure, or **fail gracefully**, whether it functions at a reduced level or fails completely, does so in a way that protects people, property, or data from injury, damage, intrusion, or disclosure.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] In computers, a program might fail-safe by executing a graceful exit (as opposed to an uncontrolled crash) to prevent data corruption after an error occurs.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] A similar distinction is made between "failing well" and "failing badly".
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] A system designed to experience **graceful degradation**, or to **fail soft** (used in computing, similar to "fail safe") operates at a reduced level of performance after some component fails.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] For example, if grid power fails, a building may operate lighting at reduced levels or elevators at reduced speeds.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] In computing, if insufficient network bandwidth is available to stream an online video, a lower-resolution version might be streamed in place of the high-resolution version.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Progressive enhancement is another example, where web pages are available in a basic functional format for older, small-screen, or limited-capability web browsers, but in an enhanced version for browsers capable of handling additional technologies or that have a larger display.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] In fault-tolerant computer systems, programs that are considered robust are designed to continue operation despite an error, exception, or invalid input, instead of failing completely.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Software brittleness is the opposite of robustness.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Resilient networks continue to transmit data despite the failure of some links or nodes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Resilient buildings and infrastructure are likewise expected to prevent complete failure in situations like earthquakes, floods, or collisions.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] A system with high failure transparency will alert users that a component failure has occurred, even if it continues to operate with full performance, so that failure can be repaired or imminent complete failure anticipated.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Likewise, a fail-fast component is designed to report at the first point of failure, rather than generating reports when downstream components fail.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] This allows easier diagnosis of the underlying problem, and may prevent improper operation in a broken state.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] A **single fault condition** is a situation where one means for protection against a hazard is defective.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] If a single fault condition results unavoidably in another single fault condition, the two failures are considered one single fault condition.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Providing fault-tolerant design for every component is normally not an option.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Associated redundancy brings a number of penalties: increase in weight, size, power consumption, cost, as well as time to design, verify, and test.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] An example of a component that passes all the tests is a car's occupant restraint system.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] While the *primary* occupant restraint system is not normally thought of, it is gravity.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] If the vehicle rolls over or undergoes severe g-forces, then this primary method of occupant restraint may fail.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Restraining the occupants during such an accident is absolutely critical to safety, so the first test is passed.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Accidents causing occupant ejection were quite common before seat belts, so the second test is passed.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] The cost of a redundant restraint method like seat belts is quite low, both economically and in terms of weight and space, so the third test is passed.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Therefore, adding seat belts to all vehicles is an excellent idea.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Other "supplemental restraint systems", such as airbags, are more expensive and so pass that test by a smaller margin.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] It would also be prohibitively costly to further double-up the main components and they would add considerable weight.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] However, the similarly critical systems for actuating the brakes under driver control are inherently less robust, generally using a cable (which can rust, stretch, jam, or snap) or hydraulic fluid (which can leak, boil and develop bubbles, or absorb water and thus lose effectiveness).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] The cumulatively unlikely combination of total foot brake failure with the need for harsh braking in an emergency will likely result in a collision, but still one at lower speed than would otherwise have been the case.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] In comparison with the foot pedal activated service brake, the parking brake itself is a less critical item, and unless it is being used as a one-time backup for the footbrake, will not cause immediate danger if it is found to be nonfunctional at the moment of application.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, on shallow gradients, the transmission can be shifted into Park, Reverse or First gear, and the transmission lock / engine compression used to hold it stationary, as there is no need for them to include the sophistication to first bring the vehicle to a halt.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] On motorcycles, a similar level of fail-safety is provided by simpler methods; first, the front and rear brake systems are entirely separate, regardless of their method of activation (that can be cable, rod or hydraulic), allowing one system to fail entirely while leaving the other unaffected.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Fault isolation to the failing component – When a failure occurs, the system must be able to isolate the failure to the offending component.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] This requires the addition of dedicated failure detection mechanisms that exist only for the purpose of fault isolation.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Recovery from a fault condition requires classifying the fault or failing component.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Faults are commonly categorized by their locality (internal or external to the system), cause (natural or human-made), duration (permanent or transient), and effect on system behavior.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Fault containment to prevent propagation of the failure – Some failure mechanisms can cause a system to fail by propagating the failure to the rest of the system.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] An example of this kind of failure is the "rogue transmitter" that can swamp legitimate communication in a system and cause overall system failure.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Firewalls or other mechanisms that isolate a rogue transmitter or failing component to protect the system are required.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Availability of reversion modes, which is the abandonment of recent changes, usually to software, that bring a system back to reasonably proper behavior and function.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] In addition, fault-tolerant systems are characterized in terms of both planned service outages and unplanned service outages.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] These are usually measured at the application level and not just at a hardware level.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] The figure of merit is called availability and is expressed as a percentage.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] For example, a five nines system would statistically provide 99.999% availability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Fault-tolerant systems are typically based on the concept of redundancy.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Research into the kinds of tolerances needed for critical systems involves a large amount of interdisciplinary work.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] The more complex the system, the more carefully all possible interactions have to be considered and prepared for.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] All implementations of RAID, redundant array of independent disks, except RAID 0, are examples of a fault-tolerant storage device that uses data redundancy.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] A lockstep fault-tolerant machine uses replicated elements operating in parallel.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] At any time, all the replications of each element should be in the same state.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] The same inputs are provided to each replication, and the same outputs are expected.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] The outputs of the replications are compared using a voting circuit.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] A machine with two replications of each element is termed dual modular redundant (DMR).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can then only detect a mismatch and recovery relies on other methods.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] A machine with three replications of each element is termed triple modular redundant (TMR).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can determine which replication is in error when a two-to-one vote is observed.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] In this case, the voting circuit can output the correct result, and discard the erroneous version.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] After this, the internal state of the erroneous replication is assumed to be different from that of the other two, and the voting circuit can switch to a DMR mode.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] This model can be applied to any larger number of replications.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Lockstep fault-tolerant machines are most easily made fully synchronous, with each gate of each replication making the same state transition on the same edge of the clock, and the clocks to the replications being exactly in phase.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] However, it is possible to build lockstep systems without this requirement.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Bringing the replications into synchrony requires making their internal stored states the same.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] They can be started from a fixed initial state, such as the reset state.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, the internal state of one replica can be copied to another replica.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] One variant of DMR is **pair-and-spare**.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Two replicated elements operate in lockstep as a pair, with a voting circuit that detects any mismatch between their operations and outputs a signal indicating that there is an error.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Another pair operates exactly the same way.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] A final circuit selects the output of the pair that does not proclaim that it is in error.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Pair-and-spare requires four replicas rather than the three of TMR, but has been used commercially.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] The approach has performance costs: because the technique rewrites code to insert dynamic checks for address validity, execution time will increase by 80% to 500%.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Recovery shepherding is a lightweight technique to enable software programs to recover from otherwise fatal errors such as null pointer dereference and divide by zero.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Comparing to the failure oblivious computing technique, recovery shepherding works on the compiled program binary directly and does not need to recompile to program.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] It uses the just-in-time binary instrumentation framework Pin.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] It attaches to the application process when an error occurs, repairs the execution, tracks the repair effects as the execution continues, contains the repair effects within the application process, and detaches from the process after all repair effects are flushed from the process state.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] It does not interfere with the normal execution of the program and therefore incurs negligible overhead.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] For 17 of 18 systematically collected real world null-dereference and divide-by-zero errors, a prototype implementation enables the application to continue to execute to provide acceptable output and service to its users on the error-triggering inputs.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] The circuit breaker design pattern is a technique to avoid catastrophic failures in distributed systems.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Redundancy is the provision of functional capabilities that would be unnecessary in a fault-free environment.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] This can consist of backup components that automatically "kick in" if one component fails.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] For example, large cargo trucks can lose a tire without any major consequences.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] They have many tires, and no one tire is critical (with the exception of the front tires, which are used to steer, but generally carry less load, each and in total, than the other four to 16, so are less likely to fail).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] The idea of incorporating redundancy in order to improve the reliability of a system was pioneered by John von Neumann in the 1950s.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Two kinds of redundancy are possible: space redundancy and time redundancy.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy provides additional components, functions, or data items that are unnecessary for fault-free operation.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy is further classified into hardware, software and information redundancy, depending on the type of redundant resources added to the system.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] In time redundancy the computation or data transmission is repeated and the result is compared to a stored copy of the previous result.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] The current terminology for this kind of testing is referred to as In Service Fault Tolerance Testing or ISFTT for short.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] There is a difference between fault tolerance and systems that rarely have problems.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] For instance, the Western Electric crossbar systems had failure rates of two hours per forty years, and therefore were highly *fault resistant*.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/fault-tolerance] But when a fault did occur, they stopped operating completely, and therefore were not *fault tolerant*.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] There is now more dependence on these systems as a result of modernization.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] For example, to carry out their regular daily tasks, hospitals and data centers need their systems to be highly available.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Availability refers to the ability of the user to access a service or system, whether to submit new work, update or modify existing work, or retrieve the results of previous work.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] If a user cannot access the system, it is considered *unavailable from the user's perspective*.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] The term *downtime* is generally used to refer to describe periods when a system is unavailable.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] As such, network resilience touches a very wide range of topics.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] In order to increase the resilience of a given communication network, the probable challenges and risks have to be identified and appropriate resilience metrics have to be defined for the service to be protected.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] The importance of network resilience is continuously increasing, as communication networks are becoming a fundamental component in the operation of critical infrastructures.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Consequently, recent efforts focus on interpreting and improving network and computing resilience with applications to critical infrastructures.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] As an example, one can consider as a resilience objective the provisioning of services over the network, instead of the services of the network itself.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] This may require coordinated response from both the network and from the services running on top of the network.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Resilience and survivability are interchangeably used according to the specific context of a given study.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] There are three principles of systems design in reliability engineering that can help achieve high availability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] In redundant systems, the crossover point itself tends to become a single point of failure.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Reliable systems must provide for reliable crossover.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] If the two principles above are observed, then a user may never see a failure – but the maintenance activity must.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] A distinction can be made between scheduled and unscheduled downtime.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Typically, scheduled downtime is a result of maintenance that is disruptive to system operation and usually cannot be avoided with a currently installed system design.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Scheduled downtime events might include patches to system software that require a reboot or system configuration changes that only take effect upon a reboot.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] In general, scheduled downtime is usually the result of some logical, management-initiated event.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Unscheduled downtime events typically arise from some physical event, such as a hardware or software failure or environmental anomaly.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] If users can be warned away from scheduled downtimes, then the distinction is useful.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] But if the requirement is for true high availability, then downtime is downtime whether or not it is scheduled.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Many computing sites exclude scheduled downtime from availability calculations, assuming that it has little or no impact upon the computing user community.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] By doing this, they can claim to have phenomenally high availability, which might give the illusion of continuous availability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] For certain systems, scheduled downtime does not matter, for example, system downtime at an office building after everybody has gone home for the night.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Availability is usually expressed as a percentage of uptime in a given year.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] The following table shows the downtime that will be allowed for a particular percentage of availability, presuming that the system is required to operate continuously.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Service level agreements often refer to monthly downtime or availability in order to calculate service credits to match monthly billing cycles.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] The following table shows the translation from a given availability percentage to the corresponding amount of time a system would be unavailable.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Availability is often quoted in terms of "nines", with 90% availability being called "one nine", 99% "two nines", 99.9% "three nines" and so on.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] As the number of nines gets larger, the availability targets get exponentially more stringent.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] The terms uptime and availability are often used interchangeably but do not always refer to the same thing.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] For example, a system can be "up" with its services not "available" in the case of a network outage.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Or a system undergoing software maintenance can be "available" to be worked on by a system administrator, but its services do not appear "up" to the end user or customer.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] A simple mnemonic rule states that *5 nines* allows approximately 5 minutes of downtime per year.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Variants can be derived by multiplying or dividing by 10: 4 nines is 50 minutes and 3 nines is 500 minutes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] In the opposite direction, 6 nines is 0.5 minutes (30 sec) and 7 nines is 3 seconds.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Another memory trick to calculate the allowed downtime duration for an " n -nines" availability percentage is to use the formula $8.64\times 10^{4-n}$ seconds per day.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] For example, 90% ("one nine") yields the exponent $4-1=3$ , and therefore the allowed downtime is $8.64\times 10^{3}$ seconds per day.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Also, 99.999% ("five nines") gives the exponent $4-5=-1$ , and therefore the allowed downtime is $8.64\times 10^{-1}$ seconds per day.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Percentages of a particular order of magnitude are sometimes referred to by the number of nines or "class of nines" in the digits.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] For example, electricity that is delivered without interruptions (blackouts, brownouts or surges) 99.999% of the time would have 5 nines reliability, or class five.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] In particular, the term is used in connection with mainframes or enterprise computing, often as part of a service-level agreement.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Similarly, percentages ending in a 5 have conventional names, traditionally the number of nines, then "five", so 99.95% is "three nines five", abbreviated 3N5.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] This is casually referred to as "three and a half nines", but this is incorrect: a 5 is only a factor of 2, while a 9 is a factor of 10, so a 5 is 0.3 nines (per below formula: $\log _{10}2\approx 0.3$ ): 99.95% availability is 3.3 nines, not 3.5 nines.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] More simply, going from 99.9% availability to 99.95% availability is a factor of 2 (0.1% to 0.05% unavailability), but going from 99.95% to 99.99% availability is a factor of 5 (0.05% to 0.01% unavailability), over twice as much.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] A similar measurement is sometimes used to describe the purity of substances.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] In general, the number of nines is not often used by a network engineer when modeling and measuring availability because it is hard to apply in formula.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] More often, the unavailability expressed as a probability (like 0.00001), or a downtime per year is quoted.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Availability specified as a number of nines is often seen in marketing documents.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] The use of the "nines" has been called into question, since it does not appropriately reflect that the impact of unavailability varies with its time of occurrence.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] For large amounts of 9s, the "unavailability" index (measure of downtime rather than uptime) is easier to handle.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] For example, this is why an "unavailability" rather than availability metric is used in hard disk or data link bit error rates.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Sometimes the humorous term "nine fives" (55.5555555%) is used to contrast with "five nines" (99.999%), though this is not an actual goal, but rather a sarcastic reference to something totally failing to meet any reasonable target.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Availability measurement is subject to some degree of interpretation.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] A system that has been up for 365 days in a non-leap year might have been eclipsed by a network failure that lasted for 9 hours during a peak usage period; the user community will see the system as unavailable, whereas the system administrator will claim 100% uptime.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] However, given the true definition of availability, the system will be approximately 99.9% available, or three nines (8751 hours of available time out of 8760 hours per non-leap year).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Also, systems experiencing performance problems are often deemed partially or entirely unavailable by users, even when the systems are continuing to function.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Similarly, unavailability of select application functions might go unnoticed by administrators yet be devastating to users – a true availability measure is holistic.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Availability must be measured to be determined, ideally with comprehensive monitoring tools ("instrumentation") that are themselves highly available.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] An alternative metric is mean time between failures (MTBF).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Recovery time (or estimated time of repair (ETR), also known as recovery time objective (RTO) is closely related to availability, that is the total time required for a planned outage or the time required to fully recover from an unplanned outage.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Another metric is mean time to recovery (MTTR).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Recovery time could be infinite with certain system designs and failures, i.e. full recovery is impossible.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] One such example is a fire or flood that destroys a data center and its systems when there is no secondary disaster recovery data center.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Another related concept is data availability, that is the degree to which databases and other information storage systems faithfully record and report system transactions.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Information management often focuses separately on data availability, or Recovery Point Objective, in order to determine acceptable (or actual) data loss with various failure events.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Some users can tolerate application service interruptions but cannot tolerate data loss.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] A service level agreement ("SLA") formalizes an organization's availability objectives and requirements.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] High availability is one of the primary requirements of the control systems in unmanned vehicles and autonomous maritime vessels.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] If the controlling system becomes unavailable, the Ground Combat Vehicle (GCV) or ASW Continuous Trail Unmanned Vessel (ACTUV) would be lost.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] On one hand, adding more components to an overall system design can undermine efforts to achieve high availability because complex systems inherently have more potential failure points and are more difficult to implement correctly.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] More advanced system designs allow for systems to be patched and upgraded without compromising service availability (see load balancing and failover).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] High availability requires less human intervention to restore operation in complex systems; the reason for this being that the most common cause for outages is human error.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] On the other hand, redundancy is used to create systems with high levels of availability (e.g. popular ecommerce websites).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] In this case it is required to have high levels of failure detectability and avoidance of common cause failures.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] If redundant parts are used in parallel and have independent failure (e.g. by not being within the same data center), they can exponentially increase the availability and make the overall system highly available.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] So for example if each of your components has only 50% availability, by using 10 of components in parallel, you can achieve 99.9023% availability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Two kinds of redundancy are passive redundancy and active redundancy.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Passive redundancy is used to achieve high availability by including enough excess capacity in the design to accommodate a performance decline.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] The simplest example is a boat with two separate engines driving two separate propellers.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] The boat continues toward its destination despite failure of a single engine or propeller.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] A more complex example is multiple redundant power generation facilities within a large system involving electric power transmission.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Malfunction of single components is not considered to be a failure unless the resulting performance decline exceeds the specification limits for the entire system.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Active redundancy is used in complex systems to achieve high availability with no performance decline.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Multiple items of the same kind are incorporated into a design that includes a method to detect failure and automatically reconfigure the system to bypass failed items using a voting scheme.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] This is used with complex computing systems that are linked.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Internet routing is derived from early work by Birman and Joseph in this area.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Active redundancy may introduce more complex failure modes into a system, such as continuous system reconfiguration due to faulty voting logic.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Fault instrumentation can be used in systems with limited redundancy to achieve high availability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Maintenance actions occur during brief periods of downtime only after a fault indicator activates.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Failure is only significant if this occurs during a mission critical period.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Modeling and simulation is used to evaluate the theoretical reliability for large systems.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] The outcome of this kind of model is used to evaluate different design options.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] A model of the entire system is created, and the model is stressed by removing components.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] Redundancy simulation involves the N-x criteria.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] N represents the total number of components in the system. x is the number of components used to stress the system.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] N-1 means the model is stressed by evaluating performance with all possible combinations where one component is faulted.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] N-2 means the model is stressed by evaluating performance with all possible combinations where two component are faulted simultaneously.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] A survey among academic availability experts in 2010 ranked reasons for unavailability of enterprise IT systems.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] A book on the factors themselves was published in 2003.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/high-availability] In a 1998 report from IBM Global Services, unavailable systems were estimated to have cost American businesses $4.54 billion in 1996, due to lost productivity and revenues.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] kubelet is responsible for the running state of each node, ensuring that all containers on the node are healthy.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] It takes care of starting, stopping, and maintaining application containers organized into pods as directed by the control plane. kubelet monitors the state of a pod, and if not in the desired state, the pod re-deploys to the same node.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Node status is relayed every few seconds via heartbeat messages to the API server.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Once the control plane detects a node failure, a higher-level controller is expected to observe this state change and launch pods on another healthy node.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] A container runtime is responsible for the lifecycle of containers, including launching, reconciling and killing of containers. kubelet interacts with container runtimes via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), which decouples the maintenance of core Kubernetes from the actual CRI implementation.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Originally, kubelet interfaced exclusively with the Docker runtime through a "dockershim".
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] However, from November 2020 up to April 2022, Kubernetes has deprecated the shim in favor of directly interfacing with the container through containerd, or replacing Docker with a runtime that is compliant with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] With the release of v1.24 in May 2022, the "dockershim" has been removed entirely.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Examples of popular container runtimes that are compatible with kubelet include containerd (initially supported via Docker) and CRI-O.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] kube-proxy is an implementation of a network proxy and a load balancer, and it supports the service abstraction along with the other networking operations.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] It is responsible for routing traffic to the appropriate container based on IP and port number of the incoming request.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, namespaces are utilized to segregate the resources it handles into distinct and non-intersecting collections.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] They are intended for use in environments with many users spread across multiple teams, or projects, or even separating environments like development, test, and production.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The basic scheduling unit in Kubernetes is a pod, which consists of one or more containers that are guaranteed to be co-located on the same node.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Each pod in Kubernetes is assigned a unique IP address within the cluster, allowing applications to use ports without the risk of conflict.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Within the pod, all containers can reference each other.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The container is the lowest level of a micro-service, which holds the running application, libraries, and their dependencies.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Kubernetes supports several abstractions of workloads that are at a higher level over simple pods.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] This allows users to declaratively define and manage these high-level abstractions, instead of having to manage individual pods by themselves.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Several of these abstractions, supported by a standard installation of Kubernetes, are described below.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] A ReplicaSet's purpose is to maintain a stable set of replica pods running at any given time.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] As such, it is often used to guarantee the availability of a specified number of identical Pods.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The ReplicaSet can also be said to be a grouping mechanism that lets Kubernetes maintain the number of instances that have been declared for a given pod.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The definition of a ReplicaSet uses a selector, whose evaluation will result in identifying all pods that are associated with it.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] A ReplicationController, similar to a ReplicaSet, serves the same purpose and behaves similarly to a ReplicaSet, which is to ensure that there will always be a specified number of pod replicas as desired.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The ReplicationController workload was the predecessor of a ReplicaSet, but was eventually deprecated in favor of ReplicaSet to make use of set-based label selectors.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Deployments are a higher-level management mechanism for ReplicaSets.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] While the ReplicaSet controller manages the scale of the ReplicaSet, the Deployment controller manages what happens to the ReplicaSet – whether an update has to be rolled out, or rolled back, etc.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] When Deployments are scaled up or down, this results in the declaration of the ReplicaSet changing, and this change in the declared state is managed by the ReplicaSet controller.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] StatefulSets are controllers that enforce the properties of uniqueness and ordering amongst instances of a pod, and can be used to run stateful applications.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] While scaling stateless applications is only a matter of adding more running pods, doing so for stateful workloads is harder, because the state needs to be preserved if a pod is restarted.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] If the application is scaled up or down, the state may need to be redistributed.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Databases are an example of stateful workloads.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] When run in high-availability mode, many databases come with the notion of a primary instance and secondary instances.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of ordering of instances is important.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Other applications like Apache Kafka distribute the data amongst their brokers; hence, one broker is not the same as another.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of instance uniqueness is important.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] DaemonSets are responsible for ensuring that a pod is created on every single node in the cluster.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Generally, most workloads scale in response to a desired replica count, depending on the availability and performance requirements as needed by the application.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] However, in other scenarios it may be necessary to deploy a pod to every single node in the cluster, scaling up the number of total pods as nodes are added and garbage collecting them as they are removed.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] This is particularly helpful for use cases where the workload has some dependency on the actual node or host machine, such as log collection, ingress controllers, and storage services.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] A Kubernetes service is a set of pods that work together, such as one tier of a multi-tier application.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The set of pods that constitute a service are defined by a label selector.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two modes of service discovery, using environment variables or using Kubernetes DNS.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Service discovery assigns a stable IP address and DNS name to the service, and load balances traffic in a round-robin manner to network connections of that IP address among the pods matching the selector (even as failures cause the pods to move from machine to machine).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] By default a service is exposed inside a cluster (e.g., back end pods might be grouped into a service, with requests from the front-end pods load-balanced among them), but a service can also be exposed outside a cluster (e.g., for clients to reach front-end pods).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Filesystems in the Kubernetes container provide ephemeral storage, by default.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] This means that a restart of the pod will wipe out any data on such containers, and therefore, this form of storage is quite limiting in anything but trivial applications.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] A Kubernetes volume provides persistent storage that exists for the lifetime of the pod itself.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] This storage can also be used as shared disk space for containers within the pod.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Volumes are mounted at specific mount points within the container, which are defined by the pod configuration, and cannot mount onto other volumes or link to other volumes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The same volume can be mounted at different points in the file system tree by different containers.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] A common application challenge is deciding where to store and manage configuration information, some of which may contain sensitive data.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Configuration data can be anything as fine-grained as individual properties, or coarse-grained information like entire configuration files such as JSON or XML documents.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two closely related mechanisms to deal with this need, known as ConfigMaps and Secrets, both of which allow for configuration changes to be made without requiring an application rebuild.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The data from ConfigMaps and Secrets will be made available to every single instance of the application to which these objects have been bound via the Deployment.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] A Secret and/or a ConfigMap is sent to a node only if a pod on that node requires it, which will only be stored in memory on the node.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Once the pod that depends on the Secret or ConfigMap is deleted, the in-memory copy of all bound Secrets and ConfigMaps are deleted as well.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Mounted within a volume accessible within the container's filesystem, which supports automatic reloading without restarting the container.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The biggest difference between a Secret and a ConfigMap is that Secrets are specifically designed for containing secure and confidential data, although they are not encrypted at rest by default, and requires additional setup in order to fully secure the use of Secrets within the cluster.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Secrets are often used to store confidential or sensitive data like certificates, credentials to work with image registries, passwords, and ssh keys.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Kubernetes enables clients (users or internal components) to attach keys called labels to any API object in the system, such as pods and nodes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Correspondingly, label selectors are queries against labels that resolve to matching objects.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] When a service is defined, one can define the label selectors that will be used by the service router/load balancer to select the pod instances that the traffic will be routed to.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Thus, simply changing the labels of the pods or changing the label selectors on the service can be used to control which pods get traffic and which don't, which can be used to support various deployment patterns like blue–green deployments or A/B testing.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] This capability to dynamically control how services utilize implementing resources provides a loose coupling within the infrastructure.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Just like labels, field selectors also let one select Kubernetes resources.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Unlike labels, the selection is based on the attribute values inherent to the resource being selected, rather than user-defined categorization.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` are field selectors that will be present on all Kubernetes objects.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Other selectors that can be used depend on the object/resource type.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Add-ons are additional features of the Kubernetes cluster implemented as applications running within it.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The pods may be managed by Deployments, ReplicationControllers, and so on.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Cluster DNS is a DNS server, in addition to the other DNS server(s) in the environment, which serves DNS records for Kubernetes services.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Containers started by Kubernetes automatically include this DNS server in their DNS searches.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] This is a general purpose, web-based UI for Kubernetes clusters.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] It allows administrators to manage and troubleshoot applications running in the cluster, as well as the cluster itself.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Container Resource Monitoring records metrics about containers in a central database, and provides a UI for browsing that data.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Kubernetes cost monitoring applications allow breakdown of costs by pods, nodes, namespaces, and labels.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] To prevent the loss of event data in the event of node or pod failures, container logs can be saved to a central log store with a search/browsing interface.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides no native storage for log data, but one can integrate many existing logging solutions into the Kubernetes cluster.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Containers emerged as a way to make software portable.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The container contains all the packages needed to run a service.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The provided file system makes containers extremely portable and easy to use in development.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] A container can be moved from development to test or production with no or relatively few configuration changes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Historically Kubernetes was suitable only for stateless services.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] However, many applications have a database, which requires persistence, leading to the creation of persistent storage for Kubernetes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Implementing persistent storage for containers is one of the top challenges of Kubernetes administrators, DevOps and cloud engineers.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Containers may be ephemeral, but more and more of their data is not, so one needs to ensure the data's survival in case of container termination or hardware failure.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] When deploying containers with Kubernetes or containerized applications, organizations often realize that they need persistent storage.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] They need to provide fast and reliable storage for databases, root images and other data used by the containers.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] In addition to the landscape, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), has published other information about Kubernetes Persistent Storage including a blog helping to define the container attached storage pattern.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] This pattern can be thought of as one that uses Kubernetes itself as a component of the storage system or service.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Container Attached Storage is a type of data storage that emerged as Kubernetes gained prominence.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The Container Attached Storage approach or pattern relies on Kubernetes itself for certain capabilities while delivering primarily block, file, object and interfaces to workloads running on Kubernetes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Common attributes of Container Attached Storage include the use of extensions to Kubernetes, such as custom resource definitions, and the use of Kubernetes itself for functions that otherwise would be separately developed and deployed for storage or data management.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Examples of functionality delivered by custom resource definitions or by Kubernetes itself include retry logic, delivered by Kubernetes itself, and the creation and maintenance of an inventory of available storage media and volumes, typically delivered via a custom resource definition.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] In Kubernetes version 1.9, the initial Alpha release of Container Storage Interface (CSI) was introduced.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Previously, storage volume plug-ins were included in the Kubernetes distribution.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] By creating a standardized CSI, the code required to interface with external storage systems was separated from the core Kubernetes code base.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Just one year later, the CSI feature was made Generally Available (GA) in Kubernetes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] A key component of the Kubernetes control plane is the API Server, which exposes an HTTP API that can be invoked by other parts of the cluster as well as end users and external components.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] This API is a REST API and is declarative in nature, and is the same API exposed to the control plane.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The API server is backed by etcd to store all records persistently.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, all objects serve as the "record of intent" of the cluster's state, and are able to define the desired state that the writer of the object wishes for the cluster to be in.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] All objects in Kubernetes are subject to the same API conventions.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API can be extended using *Custom Resources*, which represent objects that are not part of the standard Kubernetes installation.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] These custom resources are declared using *Custom Resource Definitions* (CRDs), which is a kind of resource that can be dynamically registered and unregistered without shutting down or restarting a cluster that is currently running.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Custom controllers are another extension mechanism that interact with the Kubernetes API, similar to the default controllers in the standard pre-installed Kubernetes controller manager.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] These controllers may interact with custom resources to allow for a declarative API: users may declare the desired state of the system via the custom resources, and it is the responsibility of the custom controller to observe the change and reconcile it.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The combination of custom resources and custom controllers are often referred to as a *Kubernetes* *Operator*.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The key use case for operators are to capture the aim of a human operator who is managing a service or set of services and to implement them using automation, and with a declarative API supporting this automation.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Human operators who look after specific applications and services have deep knowledge of how the system ought to behave, how to deploy it, and how to react if there are problems.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Examples of problems solved by operators include taking and restoring backups of that application's state, and handling upgrades of the application code alongside related changes such as database schemas or extra configuration settings.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Several notable projects under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation's incubation program follow the operator pattern to extend Kubernetes, including Argo, Open Policy Agent and Istio.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines the following strategies for controlling access to its API.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API server listens on a TCP port that serves HTTPS traffic, in order to enforce transport layer security (TLS) using CA certificates.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] In older versions of Kubernetes, the API server supported listening on both HTTP and HTTPS ports (with the HTTP port number having no transport security whatsoever).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] This was deprecated in v1.10 and eventually dropped support in v1.20 of Kubernetes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Users are typically expected to indicate and define cluster URL details along with the necessary credentials in a *kubeconfig* file, which are natively supported by other Kubernetes tools like kubectl and the official Kubernetes client libraries.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] *Attribute-based access control (ABAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users through the use of defined access control policies which combine attributes together.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] *Role-based access control (RBAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users based on roles that are granted to the user, where each role defines a list of actions that are allowed.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] *Webhook mode*: Queries a REST API service to determine if a user is authorized to perform a given action.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The same API design principles have been used to define an API to harness a program in order to create, configure, and manage Kubernetes clusters.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] A key concept embodied in the API is using Infrastructure as Software, or the notion that the Kubernetes cluster infrastructure is itself a resource / object that can be managed just like any other Kubernetes resources.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Similarly, machines that make up the cluster are also treated as a Kubernetes resource.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The API has two pieces – the core API, and a provider implementation.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] The provider implementation consists of cloud-provider specific functions that let Kubernetes provide the cluster API in a fashion that is well-integrated with the cloud-provider's services and resources.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Kubernetes is commonly used as a way to host a microservice-based implementation, because it and its associated ecosystem of tools provide all the capabilities needed to address key concerns of any microservice architecture.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] A common criticism of Kubernetes is that it is too complex.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] Various vendors offer Kubernetes-based platforms or infrastructure as a service (IaaS) that deploy Kubernetes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/kubernetes] These are typically categorized according to open-source, commercial or managed distributions.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] This guide is for application owners who want to build highly available applications, and thus need to understand what types of disruptions can happen to Pods.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] It is also for cluster administrators who want to perform automated cluster actions, like upgrading and autoscaling clusters.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] Pods do not disappear until someone (a person or a controller) destroys them, or there is an unavoidable hardware or system software error.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] We call these unavoidable cases *involuntary disruptions* to an application.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] Except for the out-of-resources condition, all these conditions should be familiar to most users; they are not specific to Kubernetes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] We call other cases *voluntary disruptions*.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] These include both actions initiated by the application owner and those initiated by a Cluster Administrator.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] These actions might be taken directly by the cluster administrator, or by automation run by the cluster administrator, or by your cluster hosting provider.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] Ask your cluster administrator or consult your cloud provider or distribution documentation to determine if any sources of voluntary disruptions are enabled for your cluster.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] If none are enabled, you can skip creating Pod Disruption Budgets.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] Not all voluntary disruptions are constrained by Pod Disruption Budgets.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] For example, deleting deployments or pods bypasses Pod Disruption Budgets.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] The frequency of voluntary disruptions varies.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] On a basic Kubernetes cluster, there are no automated voluntary disruptions (only user-triggered ones).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] However, your cluster administrator or hosting provider may run some additional services which cause voluntary disruptions.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] For example, rolling out node software updates can cause voluntary disruptions.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] Also, some implementations of cluster (node) autoscaling may cause voluntary disruptions to defragment and compact nodes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] Your cluster administrator or hosting provider should have documented what level of voluntary disruptions, if any, to expect.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] Certain configuration options, such as using PriorityClasses in your pod spec can also cause voluntary (and involuntary) disruptions.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] Kubernetes offers features to help you run highly available applications even when you introduce frequent voluntary disruptions.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] As an application owner, you can create a PodDisruptionBudget (PDB) for each application.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] A PDB limits the number of Pods of a replicated application that are down simultaneously from voluntary disruptions.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] For example, a quorum-based application would like to ensure that the number of replicas running is never brought below the number needed for a quorum.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] A web front end might want to ensure that the number of replicas serving load never falls below a certain percentage of the total.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] Cluster managers and hosting providers should use tools which respect PodDisruptionBudgets by calling the Eviction API instead of directly deleting pods or deployments.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] For example, the `kubectl drain` subcommand lets you mark a node as going out of service.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] When you run `kubectl drain`, the tool tries to evict all of the Pods on the Node you're taking out of service.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] The eviction request that `kubectl` submits on your behalf may be temporarily rejected, so the tool periodically retries all failed requests until all Pods on the target node are terminated, or until a configurable timeout is reached.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] A PDB specifies the number of replicas that an application can tolerate having, relative to how many it is intended to have.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] For example, a Deployment which has a `.spec.replicas: 5` is supposed to have 5 pods at any given time.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] If its PDB allows for there to be 4 at a time, then the Eviction API will allow voluntary disruption of one (but not two) pods at a time.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] The group of pods that comprise the application is specified using a label selector, the same as the one used by the application's controller (deployment, stateful-set, etc).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] The "intended" number of pods is computed from the `.spec.replicas` of the workload resource that is managing those pods.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] The control plane discovers the owning workload resource by examining the `.metadata.ownerReferences` of the Pod.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] Involuntary disruptions cannot be prevented by PDBs; however they do count against the budget.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] Pods which are deleted or unavailable due to a rolling upgrade to an application do count against the disruption budget, but workload resources (such as Deployment and StatefulSet) are not limited by PDBs when doing rolling upgrades.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] Instead, the handling of failures during application updates is configured in the spec for the specific workload resource.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] It is recommended to set `AlwaysAllow` Unhealthy Pod Eviction Policy to your PodDisruptionBudgets to support eviction of misbehaving applications during a node drain.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] The default behavior is to wait for the application pods to become healthy before the drain can proceed.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] When a pod is evicted using the eviction API, it is gracefully terminated, honoring the `terminationGracePeriodSeconds` setting in its PodSpec.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] Consider a cluster with 3 nodes, `node-1` through `node-3`.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] The cluster is running several applications.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] One of them has 3 replicas initially called `pod-a`, `pod-b`, and `pod-c`.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] Another, unrelated pod without a PDB, called `pod-x`, is also shown.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] All 3 pods are part of a deployment, and they collectively have a PDB which requires there be at least 2 of the 3 pods to be available at all times.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] For example, assume the cluster administrator wants to reboot into a new kernel version to fix a bug in the kernel.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] The cluster administrator first tries to drain `node-1` using the `kubectl drain` command.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] That tool tries to evict `pod-a` and `pod-x`.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] Both pods go into the `terminating` state at the same time.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] The deployment notices that one of the pods is terminating, so it creates a replacement called `pod-d`.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] Since `node-1` is cordoned, it lands on another node.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] Something has also created `pod-y` as a replacement for `pod-x`.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] (Note: for a StatefulSet, `pod-a`, which would be called something like `pod-0`, would need to terminate completely before its replacement, which is also called `pod-0` but has a different UID, could be created.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] At this point, if an impatient cluster administrator tries to drain `node-2` or `node-3`, the drain command will block, because there are only 2 available pods for the deployment, and its PDB requires at least 2.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] After some time passes, `pod-d` becomes available.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] Now, the cluster administrator tries to drain `node-2`.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] The drain command will try to evict the two pods in some order, say `pod-b` first and then `pod-d`.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] But, when it tries to evict `pod-d`, it will be refused because that would leave only one pod available for the deployment.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] The deployment creates a replacement for `pod-b` called `pod-e`.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] Because there are not enough resources in the cluster to schedule `pod-e` the drain will again block.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] At this point, the cluster administrator needs to add a node back to the cluster to proceed with the upgrade.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] A dedicated Pod `DisruptionTarget` condition is added to indicate that the Pod is about to be deleted due to a disruption.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] by a scheduler in order to accommodate a new Pod with a higher priority.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] In all other disruption scenarios, like eviction due to exceeding Pod container limits, Pods don't receive the `DisruptionTarget` condition because the disruptions were probably caused by the Pod and would reoccur on retry.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] The control plane might re-attempt to continue the disruption of the same Pod, but it is not guaranteed.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] condition might be added to a Pod, but that Pod might then not actually be deleted.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] In such a situation, after some time, the Pod disruption condition will be cleared.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] Along with cleaning up the pods, the Pod garbage collector (PodGC) will also mark them as failed if they are in a non-terminal phase (see also Pod garbage collection).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] When using a Job (or CronJob), you may want to use these Pod disruption conditions as part of your Job's Pod failure policy.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] Often, it is useful to think of the Cluster Manager and Application Owner as separate roles with limited knowledge of each other.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] Pod Disruption Budgets support this separation of roles by providing an interface between the roles.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/pods-disruptions] If you do not have such a separation of responsibilities in your organization, you may not need to use Pod Disruption Budgets.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The *reliability function* is theoretically defined as the probability of success.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] In practice, it is calculated using different techniques, and its value ranges between 0 and 1, where 0 indicates no probability of success while 1 indicates definite success.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] This probability is estimated from detailed (physics of failure) analysis, previous data sets, or through reliability testing and reliability modeling.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Availability, testability, maintainability, and maintenance are often defined as a part of "reliability engineering" in reliability programs.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability often plays a vital role in the cost-effectiveness of overall systems.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering deals with the prediction, prevention, and management of high levels of "lifetime" engineering uncertainty and risks of failure.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Although stochastic parameters define and affect reliability, reliability is not only achieved by mathematics and statistics.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering relates closely to quality engineering, safety engineering, and system safety, in that they use common methods for their analysis and may require input from each other.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] It can be said that a system must be reliably safe.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering focuses on the costs of failure caused by the system downtime, cost of spares, repair equipment, personnel, and cost of warranty claims.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The word *reliability* can be traced back to 1816 and is first attested to the poet Samuel Taylor Coleridge.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Before World War II the term was linked mostly to repeatability; a test (in any type of science) was considered "reliable" if the same results would be obtained repeatedly.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1920s, product improvement through the use of statistical process control was promoted by Dr.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Shewhart at Bell Labs, around the time that Waloddi Weibull was working on statistical models for fatigue.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The development of reliability engineering was here on a parallel path with quality.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The modern use of the word reliability was defined by the U.S. military in the 1940s, characterizing a product that would operate when expected and for a specified period.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] In World War II, many reliability issues stemmed from the inherent unreliability of electronic equipment available at the time and from fatigue.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Miner published a seminal paper titled "Cumulative Damage in Fatigue" in an ASME journal.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] A main application for reliability engineering in the military was for the vacuum tube as used in radar systems and other electronics, for which reliability proved to be very problematic and costly.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The IEEE formed the Reliability Society in 1948.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] In 1950, the United States Department of Defense formed a group called the "Advisory Group on the Reliability of Electronic Equipment" (AGREE) to investigate reliability methods for military equipment.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1960s, more emphasis was given to reliability testing on component and system levels.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The famous military standard MIL-STD-781 was created at that time.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Around this period also the much-used predecessor to military handbook 217 was published by RCA and was used for the prediction of failure rates of electronic components.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The emphasis on component reliability and empirical research (e.g.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] More pragmatic approaches, as used in the consumer industries, were being used.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1980s, televisions were increasingly made up of solid-state semiconductors.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Automobiles rapidly increased their use of semiconductors with a variety of microcomputers under the hood and in the dash.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Large air conditioning systems developed electronic controllers, as did microwave ovens and a variety of other appliances.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Communications systems began to adopt electronics to replace older mechanical switching systems.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Bellcore issued the first consumer prediction methodology for telecommunications, and SAE developed a similar document SAE870050 for automotive applications.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The nature of predictions evolved during the decade, and it became apparent that die complexity wasn't the only factor that determined failure rates for integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Kam Wong published a paper questioning the bathtub curve—see also reliability-centered maintenance.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] During this decade, the failure rate of many components dropped by a factor of 10.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Software became important to the reliability of systems.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] By the 1990s, the pace of IC development was picking up.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Wider use of stand-alone microcomputers was common, and the PC market helped keep IC densities following Moore's law and doubling about every 18 months.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering was now changing as it moved towards understanding the physics of failure.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Failure rates for components kept dropping, but system-level issues became more prominent.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Systems thinking has become more and more important.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] For software, the CMM model (Capability Maturity Model) was developed, which gave a more qualitative approach to reliability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] ISO 9000 added reliability measures to the design and development portion of certification.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The expansion of the World Wide Web created new challenges of security and trust.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The older problem of too little reliable information available had now been replaced by too much information of questionable value.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Consumer reliability problems could now be discussed online in real-time using data.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] New technologies such as micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS), handheld GPS, and hand-held devices that combine cell phones and computers all represent challenges to maintaining reliability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Product development time continued to shorten through this decade and what had been done in three years was being done in 18 months.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] This meant that reliability tools and tasks had to be more closely tied to the development process itself.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] In many ways, reliability has become part of everyday life and consumer expectations.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is the probability of a product performing its intended function under specified operating conditions in a manner that meets or exceeds customer expectations.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] To identify and correct the causes of failures that do occur despite the efforts to prevent them.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] To determine ways of coping with failures that do occur, if their causes have not been corrected.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] To apply methods for estimating the likely reliability of new designs, and for analysing reliability data.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The reason for the priority emphasis is that it is by far the most effective way of working, in terms of minimizing costs and generating reliable products.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The primary skills that are required, therefore, are the ability to understand and anticipate the possible causes of failures, and knowledge of how to prevent them.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] It is also necessary to know the methods that can be used for analyzing designs and data.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering for "complex systems" requires a different, more elaborate systems approach than for non-complex systems.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] These analyses must be done properly and with much attention to detail to be effective.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Consistent with the creation of safety cases, for example per ARP4761, the goal of reliability assessments is to provide a robust set of qualitative and quantitative evidence that the use of a component or system will not be associated with unacceptable risk.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The risk here is the combination of probability and severity of the failure incident (scenario) occurring.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The severity can be looked at from a system safety or a system availability point of view.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability for safety can be thought of as a very different focus from reliability for system availability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Availability and safety can exist in dynamic tension as keeping a system too available can be unsafe.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Forcing an engineering system into a safe state too quickly can force false alarms that impede the availability of the system.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] In a *de minimis* definition, the severity of failures includes the cost of spare parts, man-hours, logistics, damage (secondary failures), and downtime of machines which may cause production loss.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] What is acceptable is determined by the managing authority or customers or the affected communities.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Residual risk is the risk that is left over after all reliability activities have finished, and includes the unidentified risk—and is therefore not completely quantifiable.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The complexity of the technical systems such as improvements of design and materials, planned inspections, fool-proof design, and backup redundancy decreases risk and increases the cost.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The risk can be decreased to ALARA (as low as reasonably achievable) or ALAPA (as low as practically achievable) levels.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Implementing a reliability program is not simply a software purchase; it is not just a checklist of items that must be completed that ensure one has reliable products and processes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program is a complex learning and knowledge-based system unique to one's products and processes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] It is supported by leadership, built on the skills that one develops within a team, integrated into business processes, and executed by following proven standard work practices.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan is used to document exactly what "best practices" (tasks, methods, tools, analysis, and tests) are required for a particular (sub)system, as well as clarify customer requirements for reliability assessment.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] For large-scale complex systems, the reliability program plan should be a separate document.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Resource determination for manpower and budgets for testing and other tasks is critical for a successful program.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] In general, the amount of work required for an effective program for complex systems is large.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan is essential for achieving high levels of reliability, testability, maintainability, and the resulting system availability, and is developed early during system development and refined over the system's life cycle.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] It specifies not only what the reliability engineer does, but also the tasks performed by other stakeholders.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] An effective reliability program plan must be approved by top program management, which is responsible for the allocation of sufficient resources for its implementation.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan may also be used to evaluate and improve the availability of a system by the strategy of focusing on increasing testability & maintainability and not on reliability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Improving maintainability is generally easier than improving reliability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Maintainability estimates (repair rates) are also generally more accurate.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] However, because the uncertainties in the reliability estimates are in most cases very large, they are likely to dominate the availability calculation (prediction uncertainty problem), even when maintainability levels are very high.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] When reliability is not under control, more complicated issues may arise, like manpower (maintainers/customer service capability) shortages, spare part availability, logistic delays, lack of repair facilities, extensive retrofit and complex configuration management costs, and others.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The problem of unreliability may be increased also due to the "domino effect" of maintenance-induced failures after repairs.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Focusing only on maintainability is therefore not enough.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] If failures are prevented, none of the other issues are of any importance, and therefore reliability is generally regarded as the most important part of availability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability needs to be evaluated and improved related to both availability and the total cost of ownership (TCO) due to the cost of spare parts, maintenance man-hours, transport costs, storage costs, part obsolete risks, etc.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] But, as GM and Toyota have belatedly discovered, TCO also includes the downstream liability costs when reliability calculations have not sufficiently or accurately addressed customers' bodily risks.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Often a trade-off is needed between the two.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] There might be a maximum ratio between availability and cost of ownership.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The testability of a system should also be addressed in the plan, as this is the link between reliability and maintainability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The maintenance strategy can influence the reliability of a system (e.g., by preventive and/or predictive maintenance), although it can never bring it above the inherent reliability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The reliability plan should clearly provide a strategy for availability control.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Whether only availability or also cost of ownership is more important depends on the use of the system.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] A proper reliability plan should always address RAMT analysis in its total context.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] RAMT stands for reliability, availability, maintainability/maintenance, and testability in the context of the customer's needs.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] For any system, one of the first tasks of reliability engineering is to adequately specify the reliability and maintainability requirements allocated from the overall availability needs and, more importantly, derived from proper design failure analysis or preliminary prototype test results.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Clear requirements (able to be designed to) should constrain the designers from designing particular unreliable items/constructions/interfaces/systems.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Setting only availability, reliability, testability, or maintainability targets (e.g., max. failure rates) is not appropriate.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] This is a broad misunderstanding about Reliability Requirements Engineering.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability requirements address the system itself, including test and assessment requirements, and associated tasks and documentation.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability requirements are included in the appropriate system or subsystem requirements specifications, test plans, and contract statements.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The creation of proper lower-level requirements is critical.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The provision of only quantitative minimum targets (e.g., Mean Time Between Failure (MTBF) values or failure rates) is not sufficient for different reasons.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Compare this problem with the continuous (re-)balancing of, for example, lower-level-system mass requirements in the development of an aircraft, which is already often a big undertaking.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Notice that in this case, masses do only differ in terms of only some %, are not a function of time, and the data is non-probabilistic and available already in CAD models.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] In the case of reliability, the levels of unreliability (failure rates) may change with factors of decades (multiples of 10) as a result of very minor deviations in design, process, or anything else.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The information is often not available without huge uncertainties within the development phase.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] This makes this allocation problem almost impossible to do in a useful, practical, valid manner that does not result in massive over- or under-specification.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] A pragmatic approach is therefore needed—for example: the use of general levels/classes of quantitative requirements depending only on severity of failure effects.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Also, the validation of results is a far more subjective task than any other type of requirement.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] (Quantitative) reliability parameters—in terms of MTBF—are by far the most uncertain design parameters in any design.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Furthermore, reliability design requirements should drive a (system or part) design to incorporate features that prevent failures from occurring, or limit consequences from failure in the first place.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Not only would it aid in some predictions, this effort would keep from distracting the engineering effort into a kind of accounting work.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] A design requirement should be precise enough so that a designer can "design to" it and can also prove—through analysis or testing—that the requirement has been achieved, and, if possible, within some a stated confidence.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Any type of reliability requirement should be detailed and could be derived from failure analysis (Finite-Element Stress and Fatigue analysis, Reliability Hazard Analysis, FTA, FMEA, Human Factor Analysis, Functional Hazard Analysis, etc.) or any type of reliability testing.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Also, requirements are needed for verification tests (e.g., required overload stresses) and test time needed.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] To derive these requirements in an effective manner, a systems engineering-based risk assessment and mitigation logic should be used.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Robust hazard log systems must be created that contain detailed information on why and how systems could or have failed.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Requirements are to be derived and tracked in this way.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] These practical design requirements shall drive the design and not be used only for verification purposes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] These requirements (often design constraints) are in this way derived from failure analysis or preliminary tests.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Understanding of this difference compared to only purely quantitative (logistic) requirement specification (e.g., Failure Rate / MTBF target) is paramount in the development of successful (complex) systems.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The maintainability requirements address the costs of repairs as well as repair time.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Testability (not to be confused with test requirements) requirements provide the link between reliability and maintainability and should address detectability of failure modes (on a particular system level), isolation levels, and the creation of diagnostics (procedures).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] As indicated above, reliability engineers should also address requirements for various reliability tasks and documentation during system development, testing, production, and operation.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] These requirements are generally specified in the contract statement of work and depend on how much leeway the customer wishes to provide to the contractor.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability tasks include various analyses, planning, and failure reporting.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Task selection depends on the criticality of the system as well as cost.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] A safety-critical system may require a formal failure reporting and review process throughout development, whereas a non-critical system may rely on final test reports.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The most common reliability program tasks are documented in reliability program standards, such as MIL-STD-785 and IEEE 1332.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Failure reporting analysis and corrective action systems are a common approach for product/process reliability monitoring.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] However, humans are also very good at detecting such failures, correcting them, and improvising when abnormal situations occur.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Therefore, policies that completely rule out human actions in design and production processes to improve reliability may not be effective.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Some tasks are better performed by humans and some are better performed by machines.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Furthermore, human errors in management; the organization of data and information; or the misuse or abuse of items, may also contribute to unreliability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] This is the core reason why high levels of reliability for complex systems can only be achieved by following a robust systems engineering process with proper planning and execution of the validation and verification tasks.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] This also includes the careful organization of data and information sharing and creating a "reliability culture", in the same way, that having a "safety culture" is paramount in the development of safety-critical systems.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] For existing systems, it is arguable that any attempt by a responsible program to correct the root cause of discovered failures may render the initial MTBF estimate invalid, as new assumptions (themselves subject to high error levels) of the effect of this correction must be made.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Another practical issue is the general unavailability of detailed failure data, with those available often featuring inconsistent filtering of failure (feedback) data, and ignoring statistical errors (which are very high for rare events like reliability related failures).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Very clear guidelines must be present to count and compare failures related to different type of root-causes (e.g. manufacturing-, maintenance-, transport-, system-induced or inherent design failures).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Comparing different types of causes may lead to incorrect estimations and incorrect business decisions about the focus of improvement.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] To perform a proper quantitative reliability prediction for systems may be difficult and very expensive if done by testing.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] At the individual part-level, reliability results can often be obtained with comparatively high confidence, as testing of many sample parts might be possible using the available testing budget.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] However, these tests may lack validity at a system-level due to assumptions made at part-level testing.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] These authors emphasized the importance of initial part- or system-level testing until failure, and to learn from such failures to improve the system or part.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The general conclusion is drawn that an accurate and absolute prediction – by either field-data comparison or testing – of reliability is in most cases not possible.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] An exception might be failures due to wear-out problems such as fatigue failures.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] In the introduction of MIL-STD-785 it is written that reliability prediction should be used with great caution, if not used solely for comparison in trade-off studies.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Design for Reliability (DfR) is a process that encompasses tools and procedures to ensure that a product meets its reliability requirements, under its use environment, for the duration of its lifetime.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] DfR is implemented in the design stage of a product to proactively improve product reliability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] DfR is often used as part of an overall Design for Excellence (DfX) strategy.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability design begins with the development of a (system) model.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability and availability models use block diagrams and Fault Tree Analysis to provide a graphical means of evaluating the relationships between different parts of the system.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] These models may incorporate predictions based on failure rates taken from historical data.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] While the (input data) predictions are often not accurate in an absolute sense, they are valuable to assess relative differences in design alternatives.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Maintainability parameters, for example Mean time to repair (MTTR), can also be used as inputs for such models.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The most important fundamental initiating causes and failure mechanisms are to be identified and analyzed with engineering tools.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] A diverse set of practical guidance as to performance and reliability should be provided to designers so that they can generate low-stressed designs and products that protect, or are protected against, damage and excessive wear.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Proper validation of input loads (requirements) may be needed, in addition to verification for reliability "performance" by testing.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] One of the most important design techniques is redundancy.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] This means that if one part of the system fails, there is an alternate success path, such as a backup system.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The reason why this is the ultimate design choice is related to the fact that high-confidence reliability evidence for new parts or systems is often not available, or is extremely expensive to obtain.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] By combining redundancy, together with a high level of failure monitoring, and the avoidance of common cause failures; even a system with relatively poor single-channel (part) reliability, can be made highly reliable at a system level (up to mission critical reliability).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] No testing of reliability has to be required for this.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Redundancy can also be applied in systems engineering by double checking requirements, data, designs, calculations, software, and tests to overcome systematic failures.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Another effective way to deal with reliability issues is to perform analysis that predicts degradation, enabling the prevention of unscheduled downtime events / failures.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] RCM (Reliability Centered Maintenance) programs can be used for this.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] For electronic assemblies, there has been an increasing shift towards a different approach called physics of failure.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] This technique relies on understanding the physical static and dynamic failure mechanisms.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The material or component can be re-designed to reduce the probability of failure and to make it more robust against such variations.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Another common design technique is component derating: i.e. selecting components whose specifications significantly exceed the expected stress levels, such as using heavier gauge electrical wire than might normally be specified for the expected electric current.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Results from these methods are presented during reviews of part or system design, and logistics.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is just one requirement among many for a complex part or system.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Engineering trade-off studies are used to determine the optimum balance between reliability requirements and other constraints.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineers, whether using quantitative or qualitative methods to describe a failure or hazard, rely on language to pinpoint the risks and enable issues to be solved.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The language used must help create an orderly description of the function/item/system and its complex surrounding as it relates to the failure of these functions/items/systems.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Systems engineering is very much about finding the correct words to describe the problem (and related risks), so that they can be readily solved via engineering solutions.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Jack Ring said that a systems engineer's job is to "language the project." (Ring et al.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] 2000) For part/system failures, reliability engineers should concentrate more on the "why and how", rather that predicting "when".
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Understanding "why" a failure has occurred (e.g. due to over-stressed components or manufacturing issues) is far more likely to lead to improvement in the designs and processes used than quantifying "when" a failure is likely to occur (e.g. via determining MTBF).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] To do this, first the reliability hazards relating to the part/system need to be classified and ordered (based on some form of qualitative and quantitative logic if possible) to allow for more efficient assessment and eventual improvement.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] This is partly done in pure language and proposition logic, but also based on experience with similar items.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] This can for example be seen in descriptions of events in fault tree analysis, FMEA analysis, and hazard (tracking) logs.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] In this sense language and proper grammar (part of qualitative analysis) plays an important role in reliability engineering, just like it does in safety engineering or in-general within systems engineering.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Correct use of language can also be key to identifying or reducing the risks of human error, which are often the root cause of many failures.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] This can include proper instructions in maintenance manuals, operation manuals, emergency procedures, and others to prevent systematic human errors that may result in system failures.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability modeling is the process of predicting or understanding the reliability of a component or system prior to its implementation.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Two types of analysis that are often used to model a complete system's availability behavior including effects from logistics issues like spare part provisioning, transport and manpower are fault tree analysis and reliability block diagrams.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] At a component level, the same types of analyses can be used together with others.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The input for the models can come from many sources including testing; prior operational experience; field data; as well as data handbooks from similar or related industries.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Regardless of source, all model input data must be used with great caution, as predictions are only valid in cases where the same product was used in the same context.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] As such, predictions are often only used to help compare alternatives.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is defined as the probability that a device will perform its intended function during a specified period of time under stated conditions.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] where $f(x)\!$ is the failure probability density function and t is the length of the period of time (which is assumed to start from time zero).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability applies to a specified period of time.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] In practical terms, this means that a system has a specified chance that it will operate without failure before time $T\!$ .
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering ensures that components and materials will meet the requirements during the specified time.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Note that units other than time may sometimes be used (e.g.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is restricted to operation under stated (or explicitly defined) conditions.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] This constraint is necessary because it is impossible to design a system for unlimited conditions.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] A Mars rover will have different specified conditions than a family car.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The operating environment must be addressed during design and testing.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] That same rover may be required to operate in varying conditions requiring additional scrutiny.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Two notable references on reliability theory and its mathematical and statistical foundations are Barlow, R.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Often, knowledge of the statistical dependence between component failures is unknown or only partially constrained.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] When it is desired to model such incomplete knowledge, reliability theory allows for analyses that characterize ranges or bounds on system failure probabilities rather than unique distributions, particularly for small multi-component systems.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Quantitative requirements are specified using reliability parameters.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The most common reliability parameter is the mean time to failure (MTTF), which can also be specified as the failure rate (this is expressed as a frequency or conditional probability density function (PDF)) or the number of failures during a given period.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] These parameters may be useful for higher system levels and systems that are operated frequently (i.e. vehicles, machinery, and electronic equipment).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability increases as the MTTF increases.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The MTTF is usually specified in hours, but can also be used with other units of measurement, such as miles or cycles.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Using MTTF values on lower system levels can be very misleading, especially if they do not specify the associated Failures Modes and Mechanisms (The F in MTTF).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] In other cases, reliability is specified as the probability of mission success.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] For example, reliability of a scheduled aircraft flight can be specified as a dimensionless probability or a percentage, as often used in system safety engineering.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] A special case of mission success is the single-shot device or system.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] These are devices or systems that remain relatively dormant and only operate once.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Examples include automobile airbags, thermal batteries and missiles.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Single-shot reliability is specified as a probability of one-time success or is subsumed into a related parameter.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] Single-shot missile reliability may be specified as a requirement for the probability of a hit.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] For such systems, the probability of failure on demand (PFD) is the reliability measure – this is actually an "unavailability" number.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] The PFD is derived from failure rate (a frequency of occurrence) and mission time for non-repairable systems.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] For repairable systems, it is obtained from failure rate, mean-time-to-repair (MTTR), and test interval.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] This measure may not be unique for a given system as this measure depends on the kind of demand.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] In addition to system level requirements, reliability requirements may be specified for critical subsystems.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p01] In most cases, reliability parameters are specified with appropriate statistical confidence intervals.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The purpose of **reliability testing** or **reliability verification** is to discover potential problems with the design as early as possible and, ultimately, provide confidence that the system meets its reliability requirements.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability of the product in all environments such as expected use, transportation, or storage during the specified lifespan should be considered.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability verification is also called reliability testing, which refers to the use of modeling, statistics, and other methods to evaluate the reliability of the product based on the product's life span and expected performance.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Most product on the market requires reliability testing, such as automotive, integrated circuit, heavy machinery used to mine nature resources, Aircraft auto software.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing may be performed at several levels and there are different types of testing.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Complex systems may be tested at component, circuit board, unit, assembly, subsystem and system levels.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] (The test level nomenclature varies among applications.) For example, performing environmental stress screening tests at lower levels, such as piece parts or small assemblies, catches problems before they cause failures at higher levels.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Testing proceeds during each level of integration through full-up system testing, developmental testing, and operational testing, thereby reducing program risk.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] However, testing does not mitigate unreliability risk.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] With each test both statistical type I and type II errors could be made, depending on sample size, test time, assumptions and the needed discrimination ratio.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] There is risk of incorrectly rejecting a good design (type I error) and the risk of incorrectly accepting a bad design (type II error).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] It is not always feasible to test all system requirements.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Some systems are prohibitively expensive to test; some failure modes may take years to observe; some complex interactions result in a huge number of possible test cases; and some tests require the use of limited test ranges or other resources.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] In such cases, different approaches to testing can be used, such as (highly) accelerated life testing, design of experiments, and simulations.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The desired level of statistical confidence also plays a role in reliability testing.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Statistical confidence is increased by increasing either the test time or the number of items tested.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability test plans are designed to achieve the specified reliability at the specified confidence level with the minimum number of test units and test time.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Different test plans result in different levels of risk to the producer and consumer.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The desired reliability, statistical confidence, and risk levels for each side influence the ultimate test plan.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The customer and developer should agree in advance on how reliability requirements will be tested.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] A key aspect of reliability testing is to define "failure".
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Although this may seem obvious, there are many situations where it is not clear whether a failure is really the fault of the system.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Variations in test conditions, operator differences, weather and unexpected situations create differences between the customer and the system developer.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] One strategy to address this issue is to use a scoring conference process.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] A scoring conference includes representatives from the customer, the developer, the test organization, the reliability organization, and sometimes independent observers.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The scoring conference process is defined in the statement of work.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Each test case is considered by the group and "scored" as a success or failure.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] This scoring is the official result used by the reliability engineer.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] As part of the requirements phase, the reliability engineer develops a test strategy with the customer.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The test strategy makes trade-offs between the needs of the reliability organization, which wants as much data as possible, and constraints such as cost, schedule and available resources.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Test plans and procedures are developed for each reliability test, and results are documented.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing is common in the Photonics industry.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Examples of reliability tests of lasers are life test and burn-in.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] These tests consist of the highly accelerated aging, under controlled conditions, of a group of lasers.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The data collected from these life tests are used to predict laser life expectancy under the intended operating characteristics.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The product life span can be split into four different for analysis.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Useful life is the estimated economic life of the product, which is defined as the time can be used before the cost of repair do not justify the continue use to the product.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Warranty life is the product should perform the function within the specified time period.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Design life is where during the design of the product, designer take into consideration on the life time of competitive product and customer desire and ensure that the product do not result in customer dissatisfaction.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability test requirements can follow from any analysis for which the first estimate of failure probability, failure mode or effect needs to be justified.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Evidence can be generated with some level of confidence by testing.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] With software-based systems, the probability is a mix of software and hardware-based failures.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Testing reliability requirements is problematic for several reasons.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] A single test is in most cases insufficient to generate enough statistical data.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Multiple tests or long-duration tests are usually very expensive.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Some tests are simply impractical, and environmental conditions can be hard to predict over a systems life-cycle.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is used to design a realistic and affordable test program that provides empirical evidence that the system meets its reliability requirements.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Statistical confidence levels are used to address some of these concerns.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] A certain parameter is expressed along with a corresponding confidence level: for example, an MTBF of 1000 hours at 90% confidence level.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] From this specification, the reliability engineer can, for example, design a test with explicit criteria for the number of hours and number of failures until the requirement is met or failed.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The combination of required reliability level and required confidence level greatly affects the development cost and the risk to both the customer and producer.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Care is needed to select the best combination of requirements—e.g. cost-effectiveness.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing may be performed at various levels, such as component, subsystem and system.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] For systems that must last many years, accelerated life tests may be needed.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] A systematic approach to reliability testing is to, first, determine reliability goal, then do tests that are linked to performance and determine the reliability of the product.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] A reliability verification test in modern industries should clearly determine how they relate to the product's overall reliability performance and how individual tests impact the warranty cost and customer satisfaction.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The purpose of accelerated life testing (ALT test) is to induce field failure in the laboratory at a much faster rate by providing a harsher, but nonetheless representative, environment.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] In such a test, the product is expected to fail in the lab just as it would have failed in the field—but in much less time.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability is a special aspect of reliability engineering.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] It focuses on foundations and techniques to make software more reliable, i.e., resilient to faults.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] System reliability, by definition, includes all parts of the system, including hardware, software, supporting infrastructure (including critical external interfaces), operators and procedures.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Traditionally, reliability engineering focuses on critical hardware parts of the system.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Since the widespread use of digital integrated circuit technology, software has become an increasingly critical part of most electronics and, hence, nearly all present day systems.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Therefore, software reliability has gained prominence within the field of system reliability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] There are significant differences, however, in how software and hardware behave.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Most hardware unreliability is the result of a component or material failure that results in the system not performing its intended function.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Repairing or replacing the hardware component restores the system to its original operating state.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] However, software does not fail in the same sense that hardware fails.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Instead, software unreliability is the result of unanticipated results of software operations.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Even relatively small software programs can have astronomically large combinations of inputs and states that are infeasible to exhaustively test.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Restoring software to its original state only works until the same combination of inputs and states results in the same unintended result.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability engineering must take this into account.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] As with hardware, software reliability depends on good requirements, design and implementation.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability engineering relies heavily on a disciplined software engineering process to anticipate and design against unintended consequences.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] There is more overlap between software quality engineering and software reliability engineering than between hardware quality and reliability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] A good software development plan is a key aspect of the software reliability program.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The software development plan describes the design and coding standards, peer reviews, unit tests, configuration management, software metrics and software models to be used during software development.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] In modern distributed and microservices-based systems, reliability considerations increasingly extend beyond component-level correctness to include the behavior of applications at the business-logic level.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] It addresses scenarios in which individual system components may appear operational, while failures arise from service interactions or logic errors, potentially leading to degraded user experience or incorrect outcomes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Practices associated with application-level reliability include end-to-end observability, synthetic transaction testing, and validation of business-critical processes, complementing traditional infrastructure-focused reliability methods.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] A common reliability metric is the number of software faults per line of code (FLOC), usually expressed as faults per thousand lines of code.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] This metric, along with software execution time, is key to most software reliability models and estimates.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The theory is that the software reliability increases as the number of faults (or fault density) decreases.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Establishing a direct connection between fault density and mean-time-between-failure is difficult, however, because of the way software faults are distributed in the code, their severity, and the probability of the combination of inputs necessary to encounter the fault.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Nevertheless, fault density serves as a useful indicator for the reliability engineer.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Other software metrics, such as complexity, are also used.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] This metric remains controversial, since changes in software development and verification practices can have dramatic impact on overall defect rates.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Software testing is an important aspect of software reliability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Even the best software development process results in some software faults that are nearly undetectable until tested.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Software is tested at several levels, starting with individual units, through integration and full-up system testing.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] All phases of testing, software faults are discovered, corrected, and re-tested.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability estimates are updated based on the fault density and other metrics.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] At a system level, mean-time-between-failure data can be collected and used to estimate reliability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Unlike hardware, performing exactly the same test on exactly the same software configuration does not provide increased statistical confidence.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Instead, software reliability uses different metrics, such as code coverage.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The Software Engineering Institute's capability maturity model is a common means of assessing the overall software development process for reliability and quality purposes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Structural reliability or the reliability of structures is the application of reliability theory to the behavior of structures.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] It is used in both the design and maintenance of different types of structures including concrete and steel structures.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] In structural reliability studies both loads and resistances are modeled as probabilistic variables.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Using this approach the probability of failure of a structure is calculated.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability for safety and reliability for availability are often closely related.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Lost availability of an engineering system can cost money.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] If a subway system is unavailable the subway operator will lose money for each hour the system is down.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The subway operator will lose more money if safety is compromised.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The definition of reliability is tied to a probability of not encountering a failure.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] A failure can cause loss of safety, loss of availability or both.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] It is undesirable to lose safety or availability in a critical system.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is concerned with overall minimisation of failures that could lead to financial losses for the responsible entity, whereas safety engineering focuses on minimising a specific set of failure types that in general could lead to loss of life, injury or damage to equipment.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Safety engineering is often highly specific, relating only to certain tightly regulated industries, applications, or areas.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] It primarily focuses on system safety hazards that could lead to severe accidents including: loss of life; destruction of equipment; or environmental damage.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] As such, the related system functional reliability requirements are often extremely high.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Although it deals with unwanted failures in the same sense as reliability engineering, it, however, has less of a focus on direct costs, and is not concerned with post-failure repair actions.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Another difference is the level of impact of failures on society, leading to a tendency for strict control by governments or regulatory bodies (e.g. nuclear, aerospace, defense, rail and oil industries).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Safety can be increased using a 2oo2 cross checked redundant system.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Availability can be increased by using "1oo2" (1 out of 2) redundancy at a part or system level.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] If both redundant elements disagree the more permissive element will maximize availability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] A 1oo2 system should never be relied on for safety.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Fault-tolerant systems often rely on additional redundancy (e.g.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] 2oo3 voting logic) where multiple redundant elements must agree on a potentially unsafe action before it is performed.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] This increases both availability and safety at a system level.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] This is common practice in aerospace systems that need continued availability and do not have a fail-safe mode.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The above example of a 2oo3 fault tolerant system increases both mission reliability as well as safety.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] However, the "basic" reliability of the system will in this case still be lower than a non-redundant (1oo1) or 2oo2 system.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Basic reliability engineering covers all failures, including those that might not result in system failure, but do result in additional cost due to: maintenance repair actions; logistics; spare parts etc.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] For example, replacement or repair of 1 faulty channel in a 2oo3 voting system, (the system is still operating, although with one failed channel it has actually become a 2oo2 system) is contributing to basic unreliability but not mission unreliability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] As an example, the failure of the tail-light of an aircraft will not prevent the plane from flying (and so is not considered a mission failure), but it does need to be remedied (with a related cost, and so does contribute to the basic unreliability levels).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] When using fault tolerant (redundant) systems or systems that are equipped with protection functions, detectability of failures and avoidance of common cause failures becomes paramount for safe functioning and/or mission reliability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality often focuses on manufacturing defects during the warranty phase.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability looks at the failure intensity over the whole life of a product or engineering system from commissioning to decommissioning.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Six Sigma has its roots in statistical control in quality of manufacturing.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is a specialty part of systems engineering.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The systems engineering process is a discovery process that is often unlike a manufacturing process.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] A manufacturing process is often focused on repetitive activities that achieve high quality outputs with minimum cost and time.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The everyday usage term "quality of a product" is loosely taken to mean its inherent degree of excellence.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] In industry, a more precise definition of quality as "conformance to requirements or specifications at the start of use" is used.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Assuming the final product specification adequately captures the original requirements and customer/system needs, the quality level can be measured as the fraction of product units shipped that meet specifications.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Manufactured goods quality often focuses on the number of warranty claims during the warranty period.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality is a snapshot at the start of life through the warranty period and is related to the control of lower-level product specifications.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] This includes time-zero defects i.e. where manufacturing mistakes escaped final Quality Control.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] In theory the quality level might be described by a single fraction of defective products.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability, as a part of systems engineering, acts as more of an ongoing assessment of failure rates over many years.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Theoretically, all items will fail over an infinite period of time.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Defects that appear over time are referred to as reliability fallout.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] To describe reliability fallout a probability model that describes the fraction fallout over time is needed.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] This is known as the life distribution model.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of these reliability issues may be due to inherent design issues, which may exist even though the product conforms to specifications.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Even items that are produced perfectly will fail over time due to one or more failure mechanisms (e.g. due to human error or mechanical, electrical, and chemical factors).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] These reliability issues can also be influenced by acceptable levels of variation during initial production.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality and reliability are, therefore, related to manufacturing.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability is more targeted towards clients who are focused on failures throughout the whole life of the product such as the military, airlines or railroads.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Items that do not conform to product specification will generally do worse in terms of reliability (having a lower MTTF), but this does not always have to be the case.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The full mathematical quantification (in statistical models) of this combined relation is in general very difficult or even practically impossible.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] In cases where manufacturing variances can be effectively reduced, six sigma tools have been shown to be useful to find optimal process solutions which can increase quality and reliability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Six Sigma may also help to design products that are more robust to manufacturing induced failures and infant mortality defects in engineering systems and manufactured product.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] In contrast with Six Sigma, reliability engineering solutions are generally found by focusing on reliability testing and system design.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Furthermore, reliability engineering uses system-level solutions, like designing redundant and fault-tolerant systems for situations with high availability needs (see Reliability engineering vs Safety engineering above).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Note: A "defect" in six-sigma/quality literature is not the same as a "failure" (Field failure | e.g. fractured item) in reliability.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] A six-sigma/quality defect refers generally to non-conformance with a requirement (e.g. basic functionality or a key dimension).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Items can, however, fail over time, even if these requirements are all fulfilled.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality is generally not concerned with asking the crucial question "are the requirements actually correct?", whereas reliability is.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Once systems or parts are being produced, reliability engineering attempts to monitor, assess, and correct deficiencies.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Monitoring includes electronic and visual surveillance of critical parameters identified during the fault tree analysis design stage.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Data collection is highly dependent on the nature of the system.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Most large organizations have quality control groups that collect failure data on vehicles, equipment and machinery.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Consumer product failures are often tracked by the number of returns.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] For systems in dormant storage or on standby, it is necessary to establish a formal surveillance program to inspect and test random samples.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Any changes to the system, such as field upgrades or recall repairs, require additional reliability testing to ensure the reliability of the modification.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Since it is not possible to anticipate all the failure modes of a given system, especially ones with a human element, failures will occur.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability program also includes a systematic root cause analysis that identifies the causal relationships involved in the failure such that effective corrective actions may be implemented.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] When possible, system failures and corrective actions are reported to the reliability engineering organization.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of the most common methods to apply to a reliability operational assessment are failure reporting, analysis, and corrective action systems (FRACAS).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] This systematic approach develops a reliability, safety, and logistics assessment based on failure/incident reporting, management, analysis, and corrective/preventive actions.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Organizations today are adopting this method and utilizing commercial systems (such as Web-based FRACAS applications) that enable them to create a failure/incident data repository from which statistics can be derived to view accurate and genuine reliability, safety, and quality metrics.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] It is extremely important for an organization to adopt a common FRACAS system for all end items.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Also, it should allow test results to be captured in a practical way.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Failure to adopt one easy-to-use (in terms of ease of data-entry for field engineers and repair shop engineers) and easy-to-maintain integrated system is likely to result in a failure of the FRACAS program itself.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of the common outputs from a FRACAS system include Field MTBF, MTTR, spares consumption, reliability growth, failure/incidents distribution by type, location, part no., serial no., and symptom.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The use of past data to predict the reliability of new comparable systems/items can be misleading as reliability is a function of the context of use and can be affected by small changes in design/manufacturing.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Systems of any significant complexity are developed by organizations of people, such as a commercial company or a government agency.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability engineering organization must be consistent with the company's organizational structure.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] For small, non-critical systems, reliability engineering may be informal.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] As complexity grows, the need arises for a formal reliability function.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Because reliability is important to the customer, the customer may even specify certain aspects of the reliability organization.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] There are several common types of reliability organizations.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] The project manager or chief engineer may employ one or more reliability engineers directly.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] In larger organizations, there is usually a product assurance or specialty engineering organization, which may include reliability, maintainability, quality, safety, human factors, logistics, etc.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] In such case, the reliability engineer reports to the product assurance manager or specialty engineering manager.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] In some cases, a company may wish to establish an independent reliability organization.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] This is desirable to ensure that the system reliability, which is often expensive and time-consuming, is not unduly slighted due to budget and schedule pressures.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] In such cases, the reliability engineer works for the project day-to-day, but is actually employed and paid by a separate organization within the company.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Because reliability engineering is critical to early system design, it has become common for reliability engineers, however, the organization is structured, to work as part of an integrated product team.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Some universities offer graduate degrees in reliability engineering.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Other reliability professionals typically have an engineering, statistics, math, or physics degree from a university or college program.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Many engineering programs offer reliability courses, and some universities have entire reliability engineering programs.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] A reliability engineer must be registered as a professional engineer by the state or province by law, but not all reliability professionals are engineers.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineers are required in systems where public safety is at risk.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] There are many professional conferences and industry training programs available for reliability engineers.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/reliability-engineering-p02] Several professional organizations exist for reliability engineers, including the American Society for Quality Reliability Division (ASQ-RD), the IEEE Reliability Society, the American Society for Quality (ASQ), and the Society of Reliability Engineers (SRE).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] In computing, **scheduling** is the action of assigning resources to perform tasks.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The resources may be processors, network links or expansion cards.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The tasks may be threads, processes or data flows.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The scheduling activity is carried out by a mechanism called a **scheduler**.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Schedulers are often designed so as to keep all computer resources busy (as in load balancing), allow multiple users to share system resources effectively, or to achieve a target quality-of-service.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Scheduling is fundamental to computation itself, and an intrinsic part of the execution model of a computer system; the concept of scheduling makes it possible to have computer multitasking with a single central processing unit (CPU).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] In practice, these goals often conflict (e.g. throughput versus latency), thus a scheduler will implement a suitable compromise.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Preference is measured by any one of the concerns mentioned above, depending upon the user's needs and objectives.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] In real-time environments, such as embedded systems for automatic control in industry (for example robotics), the scheduler also must ensure that processes can meet deadlines; this is crucial for keeping the system stable.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Scheduled tasks can also be distributed to remote devices across a network and managed through an administrative back end.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The scheduler is an operating system module that selects the next jobs to be admitted into the system and the next process to run.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Operating systems may feature up to three distinct scheduler types: a *long-term scheduler* (also known as an admission scheduler or high-level scheduler), a *mid-term or medium-term scheduler*, and a *short-term scheduler*.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The names suggest the relative frequency with which their functions are performed.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The process scheduler is a part of the operating system that decides which process runs at a certain point in time.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] It usually has the ability to pause a running process, move it to the back of the running queue and start a new process; such a scheduler is known as a *preemptive scheduler*.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] If the scheduler cannot pause a running process and start a new process, the scheduler is a *cooperative scheduler*.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] We distinguish between *long-term scheduling*, *medium-term scheduling*, and *short-term scheduling* based on how often decisions must be made.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Thus, this scheduler dictates what processes are to run on a system, the degree of concurrency to be supported at any one time – whether many or few processes are to be executed concurrently, and how the split between I/O-intensive and CPU-intensive processes is to be handled.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The long-term scheduler is responsible for controlling the degree of multiprogramming.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] In general, most processes can be described as either I/O-bound or CPU-bound.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] An I/O-bound process is one that spends more of its time doing I/O than it spends doing computations.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] A CPU-bound process, in contrast, generates I/O requests infrequently, using more of its time doing computations.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] It is important that a long-term scheduler selects a good process mix of I/O-bound and CPU-bound processes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] If all processes are I/O-bound, the ready queue will almost always be empty, and the short-term scheduler will have little to do.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] On the other hand, if all processes are CPU-bound, the I/O waiting queue will almost always be empty, devices will go unused, and again the system will be unbalanced.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The system with the best performance will thus have a combination of CPU-bound and I/O-bound processes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] In modern operating systems, this is used to make sure that real-time processes get enough CPU time to finish their tasks.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Long-term scheduling is also important in large-scale systems such as batch processing systems, computer clusters, supercomputers, and render farms.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] For example, in concurrent systems, coscheduling of interacting processes is often required to prevent them from blocking due to waiting on each other.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] In these cases, special-purpose job scheduler software is typically used to assist these functions, in addition to any underlying admission scheduling support in the operating system.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Some operating systems only allow new tasks to be added if it is sure all real-time deadlines can still be met.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The specific heuristic algorithm used by an operating system to accept or reject new tasks is the *admission control mechanism*.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The *medium-term scheduler* temporarily removes processes from main memory and places them in secondary memory (such as a hard disk drive) or vice versa, which is commonly referred to as *swapping out* or *swapping in* (also incorrectly as *paging out* or *paging in*).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] In many systems today (those that support mapping virtual address space to secondary storage other than the swap file), the medium-term scheduler may actually perform the role of the long-term scheduler, by treating binaries as *swapped-out processes* upon their execution.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] In this way, when a segment of the binary is required, it can be swapped in on demand, or *lazy loaded*, also called demand paging.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The *short-term scheduler* (also known as the *CPU scheduler*) decides which of the ready, in-memory processes is to be executed (allocated a CPU) after a clock interrupt, an I/O interrupt, an operating system call or another form of signal.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Thus, the short-term scheduler makes scheduling decisions much more frequently than the long-term or mid-term schedulers – A scheduling decision will, at a minimum, have to be made after every time slice, and these are very short.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] This scheduler can be preemptive, implying that it is capable of forcibly removing processes from a CPU when it decides to allocate that CPU to another process, or non-preemptive (also known as *voluntary* or *co-operative*), in which case the scheduler is unable to *force* processes off the CPU.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Another component that is involved in the CPU-scheduling function is the dispatcher, which is the module that gives control of the CPU to the process selected by the short-term scheduler.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] It receives control in kernel mode as the result of an interrupt or system call.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The dispatcher should be as fast as possible since it is invoked during every process switch.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] During the context switches, the processor is virtually idle for a fraction of time, thus unnecessary context switches should be avoided.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The time it takes for the dispatcher to stop one process and start another is known as the *dispatch latency*.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] A **scheduling discipline** (also called **scheduling policy** or **scheduling algorithm**) is an algorithm used for distributing resources among parties that simultaneously and asynchronously request them.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Scheduling disciplines are used in routers (to handle packet traffic) as well as in operating systems (to share CPU time among both threads and processes), disk drives (I/O scheduling), printers (print spooler), most embedded systems, etc.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The main purposes of scheduling algorithms are to minimize resource starvation and to ensure fairness amongst the parties utilizing the resources.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Scheduling deals with the problem of deciding which of the outstanding requests is to be allocated resources.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] There are many different scheduling algorithms.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] In this section, we introduce several of them.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] In packet-switched computer networks and other statistical multiplexing, the notion of a **scheduling algorithm** is used as an alternative to first-come first-served queuing of data packets.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The simplest best-effort scheduling algorithms are round-robin, fair queuing (a max-min fair scheduling algorithm), proportional-fair scheduling and maximum throughput.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] If differentiated or guaranteed quality of service is offered, as opposed to best-effort communication, weighted fair queuing may be utilized.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] In advanced packet radio wireless networks such as HSDPA (High-Speed Downlink Packet Access) 3.5G cellular system, **channel-dependent scheduling** may be used to take advantage of channel state information.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] If the channel conditions are favourable, the throughput and system spectral efficiency may be increased.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] In even more advanced systems such as LTE, the scheduling is combined by channel-dependent packet-by-packet dynamic channel allocation, or by assigning OFDMA multi-carriers or other frequency-domain equalization components to the users that best can utilize them.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Earliest deadline first (EDF) or *least time to go* is a dynamic scheduling algorithm used in real-time operating systems to place processes in a priority queue.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Whenever a scheduling event occurs (a task finishes, a new task is released, etc.), the queue will be searched for the process closest to its deadline, which will be the next to be scheduled for execution.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] With this strategy the scheduler arranges processes with the least estimated processing time remaining to be next in the queue.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] This requires advanced knowledge or estimations about the time required for a process to complete.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The operating system assigns a fixed-priority rank to every process, and the scheduler arranges the processes in the ready queue in order of their priority.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Lower-priority processes get interrupted by incoming higher-priority processes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The scheduler assigns a fixed time unit per process, and cycles through them.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] If the process completes within that time slice, it gets terminated otherwise, it is rescheduled after giving a chance to all other processes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] This is used for situations in which processes are easily divided into different groups.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] For example, a common division is made between foreground (interactive) processes and background (batch) processes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] These two types of processes have different response-time requirements and so may have different scheduling needs.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] It is very useful for shared memory problems.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] A work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that always tries to keep the scheduled resources busy if there are submitted jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] In contrast, a non-work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that, in some cases, may leave the scheduled resources idle despite the presence of jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] A very common method in embedded systems is to schedule jobs manually.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] This can, for example, be done in a time-multiplexed fashion.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Sometimes the kernel is divided in three or more parts: Manual scheduling, preemptive and interrupt level.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Exact methods for scheduling jobs are often proprietary.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] When designing an operating system, a programmer must consider which scheduling algorithm will perform best for the use the system is going to see.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] There is no universal *best* scheduling algorithm, and many operating systems use extended or combinations of the scheduling algorithms above.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] For example, Windows NT/XP/Vista uses a multilevel feedback queue, a combination of fixed-priority preemptive scheduling, round-robin, and first-in, first-out algorithms.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] In this system, threads can dynamically increase or decrease in priority depending on if it has been serviced already or if it has been waiting extensively.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Every priority level is represented by its own queue, with round-robin scheduling among the high-priority threads and FIFO among the lower-priority ones.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] In this sense, response time is short for most threads, and short but critical system threads get completed very quickly.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Since threads can only use one time unit of the round-robin in the highest-priority queue, starvation can be a problem for longer high-priority threads.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The algorithm used may be as simple as round-robin in which each process is given equal time (for instance, 1 ms, usually between 1 ms and 100 ms) in a cycling list.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] So, process A executes for 1 ms, then process B, then process C, then back to process A.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] More advanced algorithms take into account process priority, or the importance of the process.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] This allows some processes to use more time than others.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The kernel always uses whatever resources it needs to ensure proper functioning of the system, and so can be said to have infinite priority.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] In SMP systems, processor affinity is considered to increase overall system performance, even if it may cause a process itself to run more slowly.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] This generally improves performance by reducing cache thrashing.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] IBM OS/360 was available with three different schedulers.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Later virtual storage versions of MVS added a *Workload Manager* feature to the scheduler, which schedules processor resources according to an elaborate scheme defined by the installation.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Very early MS-DOS and Microsoft Windows systems were non-multitasking, and as such did not feature a scheduler.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Windows 3.1x used a non-preemptive scheduler, meaning that it did not interrupt programs.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] It relied on the program to end or tell the OS that it didn't need the processor so that it could move on to another process.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] This is usually called cooperative multitasking.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Windows 95 introduced a rudimentary preemptive scheduler; however, for legacy support opted to let 16-bit applications run without preemption.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Windows NT-based operating systems use a multilevel feedback queue.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] 32 priority levels are defined, 0 through 31, with priorities 0 through 15 being *normal* priorities and priorities 16 through 31 being soft real-time priorities, requiring privileges to assign.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] User interfaces and APIs work with priority classes for the process and the threads in the process, which are then combined by the system into the absolute priority level.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The scheduler was modified in Windows Vista to use the cycle counter register of modern processors to keep track of exactly how many CPU cycles a thread has executed, rather than just using an interval-timer interrupt routine.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Vista also uses a priority scheduler for the I/O queue so that disk defragmenters and other such programs do not interfere with foreground operations.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Mac OS 9 uses cooperative scheduling for threads, where one process controls multiple cooperative threads, and also provides preemptive scheduling for multiprocessing tasks.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The kernel schedules multiprocessing tasks using a preemptive scheduling algorithm.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] All Process Manager processes run within a special multiprocessing task, called the *blue task*.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Those processes are scheduled cooperatively, using a round-robin scheduling algorithm; a process yields control of the processor to another process by explicitly calling a blocking function such as `WaitNextEvent`.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Each process has its own copy of the Thread Manager that schedules that process's threads cooperatively; a thread yields control of the processor to another thread by calling `YieldToAnyThread` or `YieldToThread`.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] macOS uses a multilevel feedback queue, with four priority bands for threads – normal, system high priority, kernel mode only, and real-time.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Threads are scheduled preemptively; macOS also supports cooperatively scheduled threads in its implementation of the Thread Manager in Carbon.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Threads are primarily of interest for applications that currently consist of several asynchronous processes.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] These applications might impose a lighter load on the system if converted to a multithreaded structure.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] AIX 5 implements the following scheduling policies: FIFO, round robin, and fair round robin.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The FIFO policy has three different implementations: FIFO, FIFO2, and FIFO3.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The round robin policy is named SCHED_RR in AIX, and the fair round robin is called SCHED_OTHER.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Linux 1.2 used a round-robin scheduling policy.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Linux 2.2 added scheduling classes and support for symmetric multiprocessing (SMP).
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] In Linux 2.4, an O(n) scheduler with a multilevel feedback queue with priority levels ranging from 0 to 140 was used; 0–99 are reserved for real-time tasks and 100–140 are considered nice task levels.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] For real-time tasks, the time quantum for switching processes was approximately 200 ms, and for nice tasks approximately 10 ms.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The scheduler ran through the run queue of all ready processes, letting the highest priority processes go first and run through their time slices, after which they will be placed in an expired queue.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] When the active queue is empty, the expired queue will become the active queue and vice versa.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] However, some enterprise Linux distributions such as SUSE Linux Enterprise Server replaced this scheduler with a backport of the O(1) scheduler (which was maintained by Alan Cox in his Linux 2.4-ac Kernel series) to the Linux 2.4 kernel used by the distribution.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] In versions 2.6.0 to 2.6.22, the kernel used an O(1) scheduler developed by Ingo Molnar and many other kernel developers during the Linux 2.5 development.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] For many kernels in this time frame, Con Kolivas developed patch sets which improved interactivity with this scheduler or even replaced it with his own schedulers.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Con Kolivas' work, most significantly his implementation of fair scheduling named Rotating Staircase Deadline (RSDL), inspired Ingo Molnár to develop the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) as a replacement for the earlier O(1) scheduler, crediting Kolivas in his announcement.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] CFS is the first implementation of a fair queuing process scheduler widely used in a general-purpose operating system.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The CFS uses a well-studied, classic scheduling algorithm called fair queuing originally invented for packet networks.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Fair queuing had been previously applied to CPU scheduling under the name stride scheduling.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The fair queuing CFS scheduler has a scheduling complexity of $O(\log N)$ , where N is the number of tasks in the runqueue.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Choosing a task can be done in constant time, but reinserting a task after it has run requires $O(\log N)$ operations, because the run queue is implemented as a red–black tree.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The Brain Fuck Scheduler, also created by Con Kolivas, is an alternative to the CFS.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) process scheduler.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The aim was to remove the need for CFS *latency nice* patches.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Linux 6.12 added support for scheduler extensions that can be added from userspace; this mechanism is known as sched_ext.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] An eBPF program can be loaded into the kernel to implement a scheduling policy.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] These schedulers can replace the default scheduler.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] FreeBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–255.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for interrupts, 64–127 for the top half of the kernel, 128–159 for real-time user threads, 160–223 for time-shared user threads, and 224–255 for idle user threads.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Also, like Linux, it uses the active queue setup, but it also has an idle queue.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] NetBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–223.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for time-shared threads (default, SCHED_OTHER policy), 64–95 for user threads that entered kernel space, 96–128 for kernel threads, 128–191 for user real-time threads (SCHED_FIFO and SCHED_RR policies), and 192–223 for software interrupts.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Solaris uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging between 0 and 169.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Priorities 0–59 are reserved for time-shared threads, 60–99 for system threads, 100–159 for real-time threads, and 160–169 for low priority interrupts.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Unlike Linux, when a process is done using its time quantum, it is given a new priority and put back in the queue.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] Solaris 9 introduced two new scheduling classes, namely fixed-priority class and fair share class.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The threads with fixed priority have the same priority range as that of the time-sharing class, but their priorities are not dynamically adjusted.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] The fair scheduling class uses CPU *shares* to prioritize threads for scheduling decisions.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] CPU shares indicate the entitlement to CPU resources.
[src:pod-disruption-budgets/scheduling-computing] They are allocated to a set of processes, which are collectively known as a project.
